{"title_page": "Have We Met", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Have We Met\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]]\n| cover      = Destroyer - Have We Met.png\n| alt        = \n| released   = January 31, 2020\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = \n| length     = 42:11\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Merge Records|Merge]]|[[Dead Oceans]]}}\n| producer   = [[John Collins (Canadian musician)|John Collins]]\n| prev_title = [[Ken (album)|Ken]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{singles\n | name      = Have We Met\n | type      = studio\n | single1 = Crimson Tide\n | single1date = October 22, 2019\n | single2 = It Just Doesn't Happen\n | single2date = November 19, 2019\n | single3 = Cue Synthesizer\n | single3date = January 8, 2020\n}}\n}}\n'''''Have We Met''''' is the twelfth [[studio album]] by Canadian indie rock band [[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]], released on January 31, 2020 by [[Merge Records]] and [[Dead Oceans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/destroyer-announces-new-album-have-we-met-shares-new-song-listen/ |title=Destroyer Announces New Album ''Have We Met'', Shares New Song: Listen |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/destroyer-new-lp-have-we-met-crimson-tide-902104/ |title=Destroyer Prep New LP 'Have We Met,' Surreal Song 'Crimson Tide' |last=Reed |first=Ryan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/10/destroyer-have-we-met-new-album-crimson-tide-stream/ |title=Destroyer announces new album Have We Met, shares \"Crimson Tide\": Stream |last=Schatz |first=Lake |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/destroyer-announces-new-album-have-we-met |title=Destroyer Announces New Album 'Have We Met' |last=Murray |first=Robin |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/track-of-the-day-destroyer-lets-his-synth-proclivities-wander-on-crimson-tide-157 |title=Track Of The Day: Destroyer lets his synth proclivities wander on 'Crimson Tide' |last=Hakimian |first=Rob |date=October 23, 2019 |website=[[The 405 (magazine)|The 405]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/destroyer-announces-new-album-with-lead-single-crimson-tide |title=Destroyer announces new album with lead single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Kenneally |first=Cerys |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[The Line of Best Fit]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/22/destroyer-shares-crimson-tide-announces-new-album-have-we-met |title=Destroyer shares \"Crimson Tide,\" announces new album ''Have We Met'' |last=Darville |first=Jordan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/10/destroyer-share-single-crimson-tide-announce-new-a.html |title=Destroyer Announce New Album, Share Lead Single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Goodridge |first=Hayden |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n''Have We Met'' was initially conceived by group leader Dan Bejar as a \"[[Y2K]] album\" with instrumentals inspired by the music of [[Bj\u00f6rk]], [[Air (band)|Air]], and [[Massive Attack]] and 90's [[trip hop]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://thequietus.com/articles/27717-destroyer-dan-bejar-interview-have-we-met-2020|title=The Quietus {{!}} Features {{!}} A Quietus Interview {{!}} Master Of Ceremonies: An Interview With Destroyer's Dan Bejar|website=The Quietus|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8549700/destroyer-have-we-met-inspirations|title=Inspirations: Destroyer's 'Have We Met'|date=2020-01-30|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The concept was quickly scrapped, with Bejar later explaining in an interview with [[stereogum]], \"It wasn\u2019t a sound that really conjured up anything to anyone.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2070605/dan-bejar-interview-destroyer-have-we-met/franchises/interview/|title=Cue Fake Drums: Dan Bejar On Destroyer's 'Have We Met'|date=2020-01-23|website=Stereogum|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Bejar characterizes the album as a \"record born of isolation\" with the motif of \"a couple individuals huddled around the glow of the computer light.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The album features a return to Bejar's [[stream of consciousness]] lyrics, previously employed on ''[[Kaputt (album)|Kaputt]]'' (2011). Bejar recorded vocals for the album at night at his kitchen table, singing into a microphone connected to his laptop running [[GarageBand]].<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/destroyer-dan-bejar-have-we-met-interview/ |title=Destroyer's Dan Bejar Serenades the Apocalypse |last=Dombal |first=Ryan |date=January 14, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> He sent the vocals as well as demos of the album's songs to longtime producer [[John Collins (musician/researcher)|John Collins]], who worked on the songs on his laptop and [[iPad]] for three months at his home in [[Seattle]], adding layers of synthesizers and rhythm sections with guitar lines by [[Nicolas Bragg]].  Collins also used fragments from previous Destroyer recording sessions to create soundscapes, including saxophone from ''Kaputt'' and trumpet from ''[[Poison Season]]'' (2015).<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Collins also produced and mixed the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadoceans.com/news/destroyer-announces-have-we-met/|title=Destroyer Announces New LP 'Have We Met' + Shares New Single/Video \"Crimson Tide\"|date=October 22, 2019|website=[[Dead Oceans]]|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mergerecords.com/have-we-met|title=Destroyer - Have We Met|website=[[Merge Records]]|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Commenting on Collins's involvement. Bejar said \"When I decided I wanted to make a record, [it was] myself on my computer, and then I\u2019d just give the whole thing to John and have him just blow it up, flesh it out -- swap out my s--tty fake drums for cool drums, and play bass on it, and make the synths cool and not generic, and make the songs move,\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Many of the finished tracks on the album the first or seconds takes that Bajar recorded.<ref name=\":2\" /> In its press release and subsequent interviews, Bejar said the album was partially influenced by 1980s films, including ''[[White Nights (1985 film)|White Nights]]'' (1985) and  ''[[Pretty in Pink]]'' (1986) in an attempt to make the album \"really film noir-ish and spooky.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kexp.org/read/2019/10/22/destroyer-announces-new-album-shares-video-first-single-crimson-tide/ |title=Destroyer Announces New Album, Shares Video for Single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Headley |first=Janice |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[KEXP-FM|KEXP]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> The album was also influenced by the minimalism of 1980s [[hip hop music]], the soundtracks of [[Korean horror]] movies, the five-hour director\u2019s cut of ''[[Until the End of the World]]'' (1991), and [[Leonard Cohen]]'s last albums.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Bejar admits the finished album was \"\u201cmore poppy than I envisioned.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Music and lyrics==\n\"University Hill\" is a reference to [[University Endowment Lands]], located west of Vancouver, where Bejar lived when he was young.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Speaking with [[The Quietus]], Bejar describes the lyrics of ''Have We Met'' as \"the most grotesque\u201d when \"compared to all other Destroyer records.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Release==\nThe album was announced on October 22, 2019 and \"Crimson Tide\" was released as its first single with an accompanying music video directed by David Galloway.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2062041/destroyer-have-we-met-crimson-tide/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"Crimson Tide\" Video |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> A North American tour in support of the album was announced the same day, beginning in February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destroyer_announces_new_album_have_we_met_plots_north_american_tour |title=Destroyer Announces New Album 'Have We Met,' Plots North American Tour |last=Gregory |first=Allie |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> \"It Just Doesn't Happen\" was released as the album's second single on November 19, 2019, accompanied by a music video featuring a snowmobile rider driving in the dark.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2065322/destroyer-it-just-doesnt-happen/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"It Just Doesn't Happen\" Video |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/destroyer-it-just-doesnt-happen-914226/ |title=Song You Need To Know: Destroyer, 'It Just Doesn't Happen' |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/destroyer-shares-new-song-it-just-doesnt-happen-listen/ |title=Destroyer Shares New Song \"It Just Doesn't Happen\": Listen |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref> \"Cue Synthesizer\" was released as the album's third single on January 8, 2020, accompanied by a music video directed by David Ehrenreich.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-destroyers-video-for-new-song-cue-synthesizer/ |title=Watch Destroyer's Video for New Song \"Cue Synthesizer\" |last=Torres |first=Eric |date=January 8, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2069190/destroyer-cue-synthesizer-video-have-we-met/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"Cue Synthesizer\" Video |last=Quinlan |first=Keely |date=January 8, 2020 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = \n| MC = 80/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/have-we-met/destroyer |title=Have We Met by Destroyer Reviews and Tracks |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/have-we-met-mw0003329197 |title=Have We Met - Destroyer |last=Deming |first=Mark |authorlink=Mark Deming |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2score = 7/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destoyer-have_we_met |title=Destroyer Have We Met |last=Blenkarn |first=Matthew |date=January 28, 2020 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/jan/30/destroyer-have-we-met-review-dead-oceans-dan-bejar |title=Destroyer: Have We Met review \u2013 synth-pop adventures in small-hours terror |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis |date=January 30, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{Cite magazine |last=Eccleston |first=Danny |title=Smash it up: Dan Bejar's elliptical 13th aims to destroy all previous long-players. |magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=316 |page=88}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/destroyer-have-we-met-review-2602414 |title=Destroyer \u2013 'Have We Met' review: irony laced retro-futurism from a master of his craft |last=Britton |first=Luke Morgan |date=January 27, 2020 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 8.5/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/destroyer-have-we-met/ |title=Destroyer: Have We Met Album Review |last=Sodomsky |first=Sam |date=January 31, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/destroyer-have-we-met-2645020821.html |title=Destroyer's 'Have We Met' Is Dan Bejar's Best Album Since 2011's 'Kaputt' |last=Bromfield |first=Daniel |date=February 4, 2020 |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Q\">{{Cite magazine |last=Segal |first=Victoria |title=The Bewitching Hour: Canadian fl\u00e2neur reintroduces his mysterious, shadowy world. |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=408 |page=121}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{Cite magazine |title=Destroyer - Have We Met |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |edition=February 2020 |issue=1336 |page=85}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10score = 8/10<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{Cite magazine |last=Anderson |first=Jason |title=Destroyer - Have We Met |magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=274 |page=27}}</ref>\n}}\nJason Anderson of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' praised the album's \"plusher aesthetic and eager melodicism\" and singled out \"Crimson Tide\", \"The Raven\" and \"The Man in Black's Blues\" as \"irresistible examples of Bejar's blend of soft rock, dream-pop and more idiosyncratic elements.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\"/> Danny Eccleston of ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' gave the album a positive review, characterizing it as \"a richly inventive 21st century version of mid-'80s UK art pop.\"<ref name=\"Mojo\"/>Writing for [[Exclaim!|Exclaim]], Matthew Blenkarn characterized the lyrics of the tracks \"The Television Music Supervisor,\" and \"Crimson Tide\" as \"dead end,\" concluding \"it makes for immersive listening, even when tracks fail to sustain themselves.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destoyer-have_we_met|title=Destroyer Have We Met|website=exclaim.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Have We Met'' track listing\n| all_writing = \n| total_length = 42:11\n| title1 = Crimson Tide\n| length1 = 6:09\n| title2 = Kinda Dark\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = It Just Doesn't Happen\n| length3 = 5:01\n| title4 = The Television Music Supervisor\n| length4 = 4:09\n| title5 = The Raven\n| length5 = 3:35\n| title6 = Cue Synthesizer\n| length6 = 3:55\n| title7 = University Hill\n| length7 = 3:39\n| title8 = Have We Met\n| length8 = 2:54\n| title9 = The Man in Black's Blues\n| length9 = 3:39\n| title10 = Foolssong\n| length10 = 5:45\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* \"Foolssong\" is stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://destroyer.bandcamp.com/album/have-we-met |title=Have We Met by Destroyer |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Have We Met''.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Have We Met |others=[[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]] |publisher=[[Merge Records]] |year=2020 |type=liner notes |id=MRG709}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Bejar]] \u2013 vocals, synthesizer\n* [[John Collins (Canadian musician)|John Collins]] \u2013 production, mixing, bass, synthesizer, drum programming, granular synthesis\n* Nicolas Bragg \u2013 guitar\n* [[Joe LaPorta]] \u2013 mastering\n* Maegan Hill-Carroll \u2013 front and back cover photos, design\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Sales chart performance for ''Have We Met''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|135|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|95|id=394469|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Portugal|39|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 2020 albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Have We Met}}\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Destroyer (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Merge Records albums]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Collins (Canadian musician)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Have We Met\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]]\n| cover      = Destroyer - Have We Met.png\n| alt        = \n| released   = January 31, 2020\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = \n| length     = 42:11\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Merge Records|Merge]]|[[Dead Oceans]]}}\n| producer   = [[John Collins (Canadian musician)|John Collins]]\n| prev_title = [[Ken (album)|Ken]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n| misc       = {{singles\n | name      = Have We Met\n | type      = studio\n | single1 = Crimson Tide\n | single1date = October 22, 2019\n | single2 = It Just Doesn't Happen\n | single2date = November 19, 2019\n | single3 = Cue Synthesizer\n | single3date = January 8, 2020\n}}\n}}\n'''''Have We Met''''' is the twelfth [[studio album]] by Canadian indie rock band [[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]], released on January 31, 2020 by [[Merge Records]] and [[Dead Oceans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/destroyer-announces-new-album-have-we-met-shares-new-song-listen/ |title=Destroyer Announces New Album ''Have We Met'', Shares New Song: Listen |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/destroyer-new-lp-have-we-met-crimson-tide-902104/ |title=Destroyer Prep New LP 'Have We Met,' Surreal Song 'Crimson Tide' |last=Reed |first=Ryan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/10/destroyer-have-we-met-new-album-crimson-tide-stream/ |title=Destroyer announces new album Have We Met, shares \"Crimson Tide\": Stream |last=Schatz |first=Lake |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/destroyer-announces-new-album-have-we-met |title=Destroyer Announces New Album 'Have We Met' |last=Murray |first=Robin |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/track-of-the-day-destroyer-lets-his-synth-proclivities-wander-on-crimson-tide-157 |title=Track Of The Day: Destroyer lets his synth proclivities wander on 'Crimson Tide' |last=Hakimian |first=Rob |date=October 23, 2019 |website=[[The 405 (magazine)|The 405]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/destroyer-announces-new-album-with-lead-single-crimson-tide |title=Destroyer announces new album with lead single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Kenneally |first=Cerys |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[The Line of Best Fit]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/10/22/destroyer-shares-crimson-tide-announces-new-album-have-we-met |title=Destroyer shares \"Crimson Tide,\" announces new album ''Have We Met'' |last=Darville |first=Jordan |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/10/destroyer-share-single-crimson-tide-announce-new-a.html |title=Destroyer Announce New Album, Share Lead Single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Goodridge |first=Hayden |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background and recording==\n''Have We Met'' was initially conceived by group leader Dan Bejar as a \"[[Y2K]] album\" with instrumentals inspired by the music of [[Bj\u00f6rk]], [[Air (band)|Air]], and [[Massive Attack]] and 90's [[trip hop]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://thequietus.com/articles/27717-destroyer-dan-bejar-interview-have-we-met-2020|title=The Quietus {{!}} Features {{!}} A Quietus Interview {{!}} Master Of Ceremonies: An Interview With Destroyer's Dan Bejar|website=The Quietus|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8549700/destroyer-have-we-met-inspirations|title=Inspirations: Destroyer's 'Have We Met'|date=2020-01-30|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The concept was quickly scrapped, with Bejar later explaining in an interview with [[stereogum]], \"It wasn\u2019t a sound that really conjured up anything to anyone.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2070605/dan-bejar-interview-destroyer-have-we-met/franchises/interview/|title=Cue Fake Drums: Dan Bejar On Destroyer's 'Have We Met'|date=2020-01-23|website=Stereogum|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Bejar characterizes the album as a \"record born of isolation\" with the motif of \"a couple individuals huddled around the glow of the computer light.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The album features a return to Bejar's [[stream of consciousness]] lyrics, previously employed on ''[[Kaputt (album)|Kaputt]]'' (2011). Bejar recorded vocals for the album at night at his kitchen table, singing into a microphone connected to his laptop running [[GarageBand]].<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/destroyer-dan-bejar-have-we-met-interview/ |title=Destroyer's Dan Bejar Serenades the Apocalypse |last=Dombal |first=Ryan |date=January 14, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> He sent the vocals as well as demos of the album's songs to longtime producer [[John Collins (musician/researcher)|John Collins]], who worked on the songs on his laptop and [[iPad]] for three months at his home in [[Seattle]], adding layers of synthesizers and rhythm sections with guitar lines by [[Nicolas Bragg]].  Collins also used fragments from previous Destroyer recording sessions to create soundscapes, including saxophone from ''Kaputt'' and trumpet from ''[[Poison Season]]'' (2015).<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Collins also produced and mixed the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadoceans.com/news/destroyer-announces-have-we-met/|title=Destroyer Announces New LP 'Have We Met' + Shares New Single/Video \"Crimson Tide\"|date=October 22, 2019|website=[[Dead Oceans]]|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mergerecords.com/have-we-met|title=Destroyer - Have We Met|website=[[Merge Records]]|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Commenting on Collins's involvement. Bejar said \"When I decided I wanted to make a record, [it was] myself on my computer, and then I\u2019d just give the whole thing to John and have him just blow it up, flesh it out -- swap out my s--tty fake drums for cool drums, and play bass on it, and make the synths cool and not generic, and make the songs move,\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> Many of the finished tracks on the album the first or seconds takes that Bajar recorded. In its press release and subsequent interviews, Bejar said the album was partially influenced by 1980s films, including ''[[White Nights (1985 film)|White Nights]]'' (1985) and  ''[[Pretty in Pink]]'' (1986) in an attempt to make the album \"really film noir-ish and spooky.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kexp.org/read/2019/10/22/destroyer-announces-new-album-shares-video-first-single-crimson-tide/ |title=Destroyer Announces New Album, Shares Video for Single \"Crimson Tide\" |last=Headley |first=Janice |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[KEXP-FM|KEXP]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> The album was also influenced by the minimalism of 1980s [[hip hop music]], the soundtracks of [[Korean horror]] movies, the five-hour director\u2019s cut of ''[[Until the End of the World]]'' (1991), and [[Leonard Cohen]]'s last albums.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Bejar admits the finished album was \"\u201cmore poppy than I envisioned.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Music and lyrics==\n\"University Hill\" is a reference to [[University Endowment Lands]], located west of Vancouver, where Bejar lived when he was young.<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Speaking with [[The Quietus]], Bejar describes the lyrics of ''Have We Met'' as \"the most grotesque\u201d when \"compared to all other Destroyer records.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Release==\nThe album was announced on October 22, 2019 and \"Crimson Tide\" was released as its first single with an accompanying music video directed by David Galloway.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2062041/destroyer-have-we-met-crimson-tide/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"Crimson Tide\" Video |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> A North American tour in support of the album was announced the same day, beginning in February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destroyer_announces_new_album_have_we_met_plots_north_american_tour |title=Destroyer Announces New Album 'Have We Met,' Plots North American Tour |last=Gregory |first=Allie |date=October 22, 2019 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref> \"It Just Doesn't Happen\" was released as the album's second single on November 19, 2019, accompanied by a music video featuring a snowmobile rider driving in the dark.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2065322/destroyer-it-just-doesnt-happen/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"It Just Doesn't Happen\" Video |last=DeVille |first=Chris |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/destroyer-it-just-doesnt-happen-914226/ |title=Song You Need To Know: Destroyer, 'It Just Doesn't Happen' |last=Ehrlich |first=Brenna |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/destroyer-shares-new-song-it-just-doesnt-happen-listen/ |title=Destroyer Shares New Song \"It Just Doesn't Happen\": Listen |last=Minsker |first=Evan |date=November 19, 2019 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref> \"Cue Synthesizer\" was released as the album's third single on January 8, 2020, accompanied by a music video directed by David Ehrenreich.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-destroyers-video-for-new-song-cue-synthesizer/ |title=Watch Destroyer's Video for New Song \"Cue Synthesizer\" |last=Torres |first=Eric |date=January 8, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/2069190/destroyer-cue-synthesizer-video-have-we-met/video/ |title=Destroyer \u2013 \"Cue Synthesizer\" Video |last=Quinlan |first=Keely |date=January 8, 2020 |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = \n| MC = 80/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/have-we-met/destroyer |title=Have We Met by Destroyer Reviews and Tracks |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/have-we-met-mw0003329197 |title=Have We Met - Destroyer |last=Deming |first=Mark |authorlink=Mark Deming |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev2score = 7/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destoyer-have_we_met |title=Destroyer Have We Met |last=Blenkarn |first=Matthew |date=January 28, 2020 |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/jan/30/destroyer-have-we-met-review-dead-oceans-dan-bejar |title=Destroyer: Have We Met review \u2013 synth-pop adventures in small-hours terror |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis |date=January 30, 2020 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{Cite magazine |last=Eccleston |first=Danny |title=Smash it up: Dan Bejar's elliptical 13th aims to destroy all previous long-players. |magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=316 |page=88}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/destroyer-have-we-met-review-2602414 |title=Destroyer \u2013 'Have We Met' review: irony laced retro-futurism from a master of his craft |last=Britton |first=Luke Morgan |date=January 27, 2020 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6score = 8.5/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/destroyer-have-we-met/ |title=Destroyer: Have We Met Album Review |last=Sodomsky |first=Sam |date=January 31, 2020 |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/destroyer-have-we-met-2645020821.html |title=Destroyer's 'Have We Met' Is Dan Bejar's Best Album Since 2011's 'Kaputt' |last=Bromfield |first=Daniel |date=February 4, 2020 |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Q\">{{Cite magazine |last=Segal |first=Victoria |title=The Bewitching Hour: Canadian fl\u00e2neur reintroduces his mysterious, shadowy world. |magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=408 |page=121}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{Cite magazine |title=Destroyer - Have We Met |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |edition=February 2020 |issue=1336 |page=85}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10score = 8/10<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{Cite magazine |last=Anderson |first=Jason |title=Destroyer - Have We Met |magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |edition=March 2020 |issue=274 |page=27}}</ref>\n}}\nJason Anderson of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' praised the album's \"plusher aesthetic and eager melodicism\" and singled out \"Crimson Tide\", \"The Raven\" and \"The Man in Black's Blues\" as \"irresistible examples of Bejar's blend of soft rock, dream-pop and more idiosyncratic elements.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\"/> Danny Eccleston of ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' gave the album a positive review, characterizing it as \"a richly inventive 21st century version of mid-'80s UK art pop.\"<ref name=\"Mojo\"/>Writing for [[Exclaim!|Exclaim]], Matthew Blenkarn characterized the lyrics of the tracks \"The Television Music Supervisor,\" and \"Crimson Tide\" as \"dead end,\" concluding \"it makes for immersive listening, even when tracks fail to sustain themselves.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/destoyer-have_we_met|title=Destroyer Have We Met|website=exclaim.ca|language=en-ca|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Have We Met'' track listing\n| all_writing = \n| total_length = 42:11\n| title1 = Crimson Tide\n| length1 = 6:09\n| title2 = Kinda Dark\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = It Just Doesn't Happen\n| length3 = 5:01\n| title4 = The Television Music Supervisor\n| length4 = 4:09\n| title5 = The Raven\n| length5 = 3:35\n| title6 = Cue Synthesizer\n| length6 = 3:55\n| title7 = University Hill\n| length7 = 3:39\n| title8 = Have We Met\n| length8 = 2:54\n| title9 = The Man in Black's Blues\n| length9 = 3:39\n| title10 = Foolssong\n| length10 = 5:45\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* \"Foolssong\" is stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://destroyer.bandcamp.com/album/have-we-met |title=Have We Met by Destroyer |website=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Have We Met''.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Have We Met |others=[[Destroyer (band)|Destroyer]] |publisher=[[Merge Records]] |year=2020 |type=liner notes |id=MRG709}}</ref>\n* [[Dan Bejar]] \u2013 vocals, synthesizer\n* [[John Collins (Canadian musician)|John Collins]] \u2013 production, mixing, bass, synthesizer, drum programming, granular synthesis\n* Nicolas Bragg \u2013 guitar\n* [[Joe LaPorta]] \u2013 mastering\n* Maegan Hill-Carroll \u2013 front and back cover photos, design\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Sales chart performance for ''Have We Met''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|135|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|95|id=394469|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Portugal|39|artist=Destroyer|album=Have We Met|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 2020 albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Destroyer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Have We Met}}\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Destroyer (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Merge Records albums]]\n[[Category:Dead Oceans albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Collins (Canadian musician)]]\n", "name_user": "Jake78541", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a citation to a sentence that I had in an earlier edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Have_We_Met"}
{"title_page": "United States one-dollar bill", "text_new": "{{For|the U.S. one-dollar coin|United States dollar coin}}\n{{morefootnotes|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox banknote\n| denomination        = One [[United States dollar|dollar]]\n| country             = United States\n| value               = $1\n| width_mm            = 6.14 inches \u2248 156.1\n| height_mm           = 2.61 inches \u2248 66.3\n| thickness_mm        = 0.109\n| weight_g            = Approx. 1<ref>{{cite web|author1=U.S. Currency Education Program|title=Weight of a US Banknote|url=https://www.uscurrency.gov/content/weight-banknote|website=uscurrency.gov|publisher=US Federal Reserve|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n| paper_type          = 75% cotton<br />25% linen<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uscurrency.gov/history-american-currency|title=The History of American Currency - U.S. Currency Education Program|publisher=}}</ref>\n| years_of_printing   = 1929 \u2013 present (Small size)\n| obverse             = US one dollar bill, obverse, series 2009.jpg\n| adsaffs Design      = [[George Washington]]\n| obverse_design    = [[George Washington]]\n| obverse_design_date = 1963\n| reverse             = US one dollar bill, reverse, series 2009.jpg\n| reverse_design      = [[Great Seal of the United States]]\n| reverse_designer    =\n| reverse_design_date = 1935\n}}\nThe '''United States one-dollar bill''' ($1) since 1876 has been the lowest value [[Denomination (currency)|denomination]] of [[United States dollar|United States paper currency]]. An image of the first [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] (1789\u20131797), [[George Washington]], based on the ''[[Athenaeum Portrait]]'', a 1796 painting by [[Gilbert Stuart]], is currently featured on the [[obverse]], and the [[Great Seal of the United States]] is featured on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]]. The one-dollar bill has the oldest overall design of all U.S. currency currently being produced (The current [[United States two-dollar bill|two-dollar bill]] obverse design dates from 1928, while the reverse appeared in 1976). The obverse design of the dollar bill seen today debuted in 1963 (the reverse in 1935) when it was first issued as a [[Federal Reserve Note]] (previously, one dollar bills were [[Silver certificate (United States)|Silver Certificates]]).\n\nThe inclusion of the motto, \"[[In God We Trust]],\" on all currency was required by law in 1955, and first appeared on [[Banknote|paper money]] in 1957.\n\nThe [[Federal Reserve]] says the average life of a $1 bill in [[Circulation_(currency)|circulation]] is 5.8 years before it is replaced because of wear.<ref>{{cite web| publisher = Federal Reserve|title=How long is the life span of U.S. paper money?|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/faqs/how-long-is-the-life-span-of-us-paper-money.htm}}</ref> Approximately 42% of all U.S. currency produced in 2009 were one-dollar bills.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Bureau of Engraving and Printing|title=1$ Note|url=http://www.moneyfactory.gov/small1denom.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216014938/http://www.moneyfactory.gov/small1denom.html|archivedate=2013-02-16}}</ref>\nAs of 2017, there were 12.1 billion one-dollar bills in circulation worldwide <ref>https://monstertubenetwork.com/hidden-facts-that-will-surprise-you-about-the-one-dollar-bill/</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nJOJO RABBIT HAS OOPSIE POOPSIES AND DIAPERS ON HIS BUM!!!!!\n\n\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1862-Fr-16c.jpg|thumb|250px|left|First $1 bill issued in 1862 as a Legal Tender Note]]\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1880-Fr-29.jpg|thumb|250px|Series 1880 $1 [[United States Note|Legal Tender]]]]\n[[File:US-$1-SC-1886-Fr-217.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Series of 1886 $1 Silver Certificate featuring [[Martha Washington]]]]\n[[File:US-$1-SC-1896-Fr-224-(3923429).jpg|thumb|250px|Famous 1896 \"[[Educational Series]]\" $1 Silver Certificate]]\n''({{small|approximately}} 7\u215c \u00d7 3\u215b in \u2245 187 \u00d7 79 &nbsp;mm)''\n* '''1862''': The first one-dollar bill was issued as a Legal Tender Note ([[United States Note]]) with a portrait of [[Salmon P. Chase]], the [[Secretary of the Treasury]] under President [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Tulane University|title=Salmon P. Chase|url=http://www.tulane.edu/~latner/Chase.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231131605/http://www.tulane.edu/~latner/Chase.html|archivedate=2006-12-31}}</ref><ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p56</ref>\n* '''1869''': The $1 United States Note was redesigned with a portrait of [[George Washington]] in the center and a [[Vignetting|vignette]] of [[Christopher Columbus]] sighting land to the left. The obverse of the note also featured overprinting of the word ONE numerous times in very small green type and blue tinting of the paper. Although this note is technically a United States Note, {{sc|TREASURY NOTE}} appeared on it instead of {{sc|UNITED STATES NOTE}}.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p57</ref>\n* '''1874''': The Series of 1869 United States Note was revised. Changes on the obverse included removing the green and blue tinting, adding a red floral design around the word {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}}, and changing the term {{sc|TREASURY NOTE}} to {{sc|UNITED STATES NOTE}}. The reverse was completely redesigned. This note was also issued as Series of 1875 and 1878.<ref name=\"GuideBook\">A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p58</ref>\n* '''1880''': The red floral design around the words {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}} and {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}} on the United States Note was removed and replaced with a large red seal. Later versions also had blue serial numbers and a small seal moved to the left side of the note.<ref name=\"GuideBook\" />\n* '''1886''': The first woman to appear on U.S. currency, [[Martha Washington]], was featured on the $1 [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificate]]. The reverse of the note featured an ornate design that occupied the entire note, excluding the borders.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p61</ref>\n* '''1890''': One-dollar Treasury or \"Coin Notes\" were issued for government purchases of silver bullion from the silver mining industry. The reverse featured the large word {{sc|ONE}} in the center surrounded by an ornate design that occupied almost the entire note.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 65</ref>\n* '''1891''': The reverse of the Series of 1890 Treasury Note was redesigned because the treasury felt that it was too \"busy,\" which would make it too easy to counterfeit. More open space was incorporated into the new design. The obverse was largely unchanged.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 66</ref>\n* '''1896''': The famous \"[[Educational Series]]\" Silver Certificate was issued. The entire obverse was covered with artwork of [[Allegory|allegorical]] figures representing \"history instructing youth\" in front of [[Washington D.C.]] The reverse featured portraits of George and Martha Washington surrounded by an ornate design that occupied almost the entire note.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 62\u201363</ref>\n* '''1899''': The $1 Silver Certificate was again redesigned. The obverse featured a vignette of the [[United States Capitol]] behind a [[bald eagle]] perched on an [[Flag of the United States|American flag]]. Below that were small portraits of [[Abraham Lincoln]] to the left and [[Ulysses S. Grant]] to the right.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 63</ref>\n* '''1917''': The obverse of the $1 United States Note was changed slightly with the removal of ornamental frames that surrounded the serial numbers.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 59</ref>\n* '''1918''': The only large-sized, Federal Reserve Note-like $1 bill was issued as a [[Federal Reserve Bank Note]] (not to be confused with [[Federal Reserve Note]]s). Each note was an obligation of the issuing Federal Reserve Bank and could only be redeemed at that corresponding bank. The obverse of the note featured a borderless portrait of George Washington to the left and wording in the entire center. The reverse featured a bald eagle in flight clutching an [[American flag]].<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 66\u201367</ref>\n* '''1923''': Both the one-dollar [[United States Note]] and Silver Certificate were redesigned. Both notes featured the same reverse and an almost identical obverse with the same border design and portrait of George Washington. The only difference between the two notes was the color of ink used for the numeral 1 crossed by the word {{sc|DOLLAR}}, [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury seal]], and serial numbers along with the wording of the obligations. These dollar bills were the first and only large-size notes with a standardized design for different types of notes of the same denomination; this same concept would later be used on small-size notes.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 59, 64</ref>\n\n===Small size notes===\n[[File:First Small Size Silver Certificate (face, 1928).jpg|thumb|250px|The first small-size $1 Silver Certificate.]]\n[[File:US $1 1928 Silver Certificate reverse.jpg|thumb|250px|Common reverse of $1 Silver Certificates (Series of 1928-1934) and $1 United States Notes ([[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]]), commonly referred to as \"Funnybacks\"]]\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1928-Fr.1500.jpg|thumb|250px|The first small-size $1 United States Banknote printed.]]\n''(6.14 length \u00d7 2.61 width\u00d7 0.0043 in thickness  = 156 \u00d7 66.3 \u00d7 0.11&nbsp;mm)''\n\nIn 1928, all currency was changed to the size which is familiar today. The first one-dollar bills were issued as [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificates]] under [[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]]. The Treasury seal and serial numbers were dark blue. The obverse was nearly identical to the Series of 1923 $1 silver certificate, but the Treasury seal featured spikes around it and a large gray {{sc|ONE}} replaced the blue \"{{small|1 DOLLAR}}.\" The reverse, too, had the same border design as the Series of 1923 $1 bill, but the center featured a large ornate {{sc|ONE}} superimposed by {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}}. These are commonly known as \"Funnybacks\" due to the rather odd-looking \"ONE\" on the reverse. These $1 silver certificates were issued until 1934.\n\nIn 1933, [[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]] $1 [[United States Note]]s were issued to supplement the supply of $1 Silver Certificates. Its Treasury seal and serial numbers were red and there was different wording on the obverse of the note. However, a month after their production, it was realized that there would be no real need for these notes and production was stopped. A small number of these $1 bills entered circulation and the rest were kept in Treasury vaults until 1949 when they were issued in [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcurrencyvalues.com/1928_one_dollar_red_seal/|title=Series of 1928 One Dollar Red Seal United States Note \u2013 Values and Pricing - Sell Old Currency|website=OldCurrencyValues.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the design of the $1 silver certificate was changed.  This occurred with that year's passage of the Silver Purchase Act, which led to a large increase in dollar bills backed by that metal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://encyclopedia-of-money.blogspot.com/2012/05/silver-purchase-act-of-1934-united.html|title=Encyclopedia of Money: Silver Purchase Act of 1934 (United States)|website=encyclopedia-of-money.Blogspot.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>  Under Washington's portrait, {{sc|ONE SILVER DOLLAR}} was changed to {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}}. The Treasury seal was moved to the right and superimposed over {{sc|ONE}}, and a blue numeral 1 was added to the left. The reverse remained the same.\n\nA year later, in 1935, the design of the one-dollar bill was changed again. On the obverse, the blue numeral 1 was changed to gray and made smaller, the gray {{sc|ONE}} to the right was removed, the Treasury seal was made smaller and superimposed by {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}}, and a stylized {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}} was added over the treasury seal. The reverse was also changed to its current design, except for the absence of {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}.\n\n[[File:US $1 1935A North Africa Silver Certificate.jpg|thumb|250px|Special issue $1 Silver Certificate for Allied troops in North Africa]]\n\n[[World War II]] brought about [[Hawaii overprint note|special issues of one-dollar bills in 1942.]]\nSpecial $1 Silver Certificates were issued for [[Hawaii]] in case of a Japanese invasion. {{sc|HAWAII}} was printed vertically on the left and right side of the obverse and also horizontally across the reverse. The seal and serial numbers were changed to brown. Special Silver Certificates were also issued as payment for Allied troops in North Africa about to begin their assault into Europe. The only difference on these one-dollar bills was a yellow instead of blue seal. Both of these types of notes could be declared worthless if they fell into enemy hands.\n\nThe next change came in 1957 when the $1 bill became the first piece of paper U.S. currency to bear the motto {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}; it was added over the word {{sc|ONE}} on the reverse. Initially the [[Bureau of Engraving and Printing|BEP]] began printing the motto on notes printed with the new 32 note press, but soon Series of 1935G bills printed on an 18 note press featured the motto.\n\nThe final production of $1 Silver Certificates occurred in late 1963. In 1964, the redemption of Silver Certificates for silver coin ended and in 1968 the redemption of Silver Certificates for silver bullion ended.\n\nProduction of one-dollar [[Federal Reserve Note]]s was undertaken in late 1963 to replace the soon-to-be obsolete $1 Silver Certificate. The design on the reverse remained the same, but the border design on the obverse underwent considerable modification, as the mostly abstract filigrees were replaced with designs that were mostly botanical in nature. In addition, the word \"one,\" which appeared eight times around the border in small type, was eliminated.  The serial numbers and treasury seal were printed in green ink. This was the first time the one-dollar bill was printed as a Federal Reserve Note.\n\nThe first change since then came in 1969, when the $1 was among all denominations of Federal Reserve Notes to feature the new [[Symbols of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury seal]], with English wording instead of Latin.<ref>http://www.onedollarbill.org/history.html</ref>\n\nThe $1 bill became the first denomination printed at the new Western Currency Facility in February 1991, when a shipment of 3.2 million [[Replacement banknote|star notes]] from the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas|Dallas FRB]] was produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uspapermoney.info/groups/f1988as.txt |title=data|website=uspapermoney.info}}</ref>\n\nThough bill denominations of $5 and higher have been redesigned twice since 1995 as part of ongoing anti-counterfeiting efforts, there are currently no plans to redesign the $1 or $2 bills.\n\n====Experimental issues====\n{{Main|Web notes}}\nSince 1933, the one-dollar bill has been the exclusive experimental denomination among circulating US currency (except for the Natick experiment in 1981, see below). The first experiment was conducted in January and February of that year to assess the effects of using different ratios of cotton to linen in the make-up of the bills. Series 1928A and 1928B $1 silver certificates with serial number block letters X-B and Y-B were used as the experimental group; the Z-B block was used as the control group. The results of the experiment were inconclusive.\n\nIn 1937, another test was conducted, similar in style to the 1933 experiment. This test used Series 1935 one-dollar bills. The particular notes used in this experiment can be identified by their serial numbers. Notes ranging from A00000001B to A06180000B and B00000001B\u2013B03300000B were the experimental group and notes ranging from C00000001B to C03300000B were part of the control group. No conclusive results were found.\n\nA better known test was done in 1942 during World War II to test alternative types of paper. This was a precautionary measure in case the current type of paper supply could not be maintained. Series 1935A notes made of the special paper and were printed with a red \"S\" to the right of the treasury seal, while notes of the control group were printed with a red ''R''. Because they have some collector value, fake red S's and R's have been applied to regular Series 1935A notes to try to pass them at a higher value; checking a note's serial numbers can prevent this. Serial numbers of the R group range from S70884001C to S72068000C and serial numbers of the S group range from S73884001C to S75068000C.\n\nSometime in the early to mid-1960s, the BEP experimented with a new firm, the Gilbert Paper Company, to see if they could duplicate the usual paper production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coinbooks.org/esylum_v15n22a21.html|title=THE GILBERT PAPER CO $1 FEDERAL RESERVE NOTES, SERIES 1963|website=www.CoinBooks.org|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref> The BEP selected a series of notes printed by the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia|Philadelphia FRB]] as the test subjects. Serial numbers for this group range from C60800001A to C61440000A.\n\nIn August 1981, a similar experiment occurred during production of Series 1977A, when the BEP printed a few print runs on Natick paper. They included a regular run and a star note run from the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond|Richmond FRB]], with serial numbers ranging from E76800001H through E80640000H and E07052001* through E07680000* (note that many sources incorrectly identify the star range as Philadelphia instead of Richmond). One print run of $10 star notes, also from Richmond, was included in this paper test, making it so far the only experimental printing not exclusive to the $1.\n\nOne-dollar bills were again the subject of experimentation in May 1992, when the BEP began to test a [[Offset printing#Web-fed litho|web-fed]] [[Intaglio (printmaking)|Intaglio]] printing press. Because of a need for greater quantities of $1 FRNs, the BEP sent out REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS (RFP) (year 1985) NO. BEP-85-73 to procure a web-fed intaglio printing press to dramatically increase the production of currency notes within the confines of their current (1985) 14th & C street facility. Instead of printing one side of a square sheet of 32 notes at a time, the web-fed press used 96 engraved images or plate-cylinder to print the back of the note, then another 96 image engraved plate-cylinder to print the front of the note. Both sides of notes were printed from a continuous roll of paper. The Alexander-Hamilton intaglio Web press printed both sides of intaglio at the same time. The web-press was designed as a full-blown production press as opposed to an experimental press. The notes were issued in Series 1988A, 1993, and 1995. Because of mechanical problems and operator error, as well as the sometimes poor quality of the notes, production was ended in July 1996. Web notes can be identified by the back plate number next to {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}} and the removal of face check letters and quadrant numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspapermoney.info/general/webs.html|title=USPaperMoney.Info: Web Notes|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Series dates===\n\n====Small size====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Type\n! Series\n! [[Treasurer of the United States|Treasurer]]\n! [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary]]\n! [[Symbols of the United States Department of the Treasury|Seal]]\n|-\n| [[Legal Tender Note]]\n| 1928\n| [[W. O. Woods|Woods]] || [[William H. Woodin|Woodin]] || Red\n|-\n| [[Silver Certificate]]\n| 1928\n| [[Harold Theodore Tate|Tate]] || [[Andrew Mellon|Mellon]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928A\n| Woods || Mellon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928B\n| Woods || [[Ogden L. Mills|Mills]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928C\n| Woods || Woodin || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928D\n| [[William Alexander Julian|Julian]] || Woodin || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928E\n| Julian || [[Henry Morgenthau, Jr.|Morgenthau]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1934\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A Hawaii\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Brown\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A North Africa\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Yellow\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935B\n| Julian || [[Fred M. Vinson|Vinson]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935C\n| Julian || [[John Wesley Snyder (US Cabinet Secretary)|Snyder]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935D\n| [[Georgia Neese Clark|Clark]] || Snyder || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935E\n| [[Ivy Baker Priest|Priest]] || [[George M. Humphrey|Humphrey]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935F\n| Priest || [[Robert B. Anderson|Anderson]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935G\n| [[Elizabeth Rudel Smith|Smith]] || [[C. Douglas Dillon|Dillon]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935G Motto\n| Smith || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935H\n| Granahan || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957\n| Priest || Anderson || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957A\n| Smith || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957B\n| Granahan || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n|[[Federal Reserve Note]]\n| 1963\n| Smith || Dillon || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1963A\n| Granahan || [[Henry H. Fowler|Fowler]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1963B\n| Granahan || [[Joseph W. Barr|Barr]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969\n| [[Dorothy Andrews Elston Kabis|Elston]] || [[David M. Kennedy|Kennedy]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969A\n| [[Dorothy Andrews Elston Kabis|Kabis]] || Kennedy || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969B\n| Kabis || [[John Connally|Connally]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969C\n| [[Romana Acosta Ba\u00f1uelos|Ba\u00f1uelos]] || Connally || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969D\n| Ba\u00f1uelos || [[George Shultz|Shultz]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1974\n| [[Francine Irving Neff|Neff]] || [[William E. Simon|Simon]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1977\n| [[Azie Taylor Morton|Morton]] || [[W. Michael Blumenthal|Blumenthal]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1977A\n| Morton || [[G. William Miller|Miller]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1981\n| [[Angela Marie Buchanan|Buchanan]] || [[Donald Regan|Regan]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1981A\n| [[Katherine D. Ortega|Ortega]] || Regan || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1985\n| Ortega || [[James Baker|Baker]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1988\n| Ortega || [[Nicholas F. Brady|Brady]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1988A\n| [[Catalina Vasquez Villalpando|Villalpando]] || Brady || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1993\n| [[Mary Ellen Withrow|Withrow]] || [[Lloyd Bentsen|Bentsen]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1995\n| Withrow || [[Robert E. Rubin|Rubin]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1999\n| Withrow || [[Lawrence Summers|Summers]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2001\n| [[Rosario Marin|Marin]] || [[Paul H. O'Neill|O'Neill]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2003\n| Marin || [[John W. Snow|Snow]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2003A\n| [[Anna Escobedo Cabral|Cabral]] || Snow || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2006\n| Cabral || [[Henry Paulson|Paulson]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2009\n| [[Rosa Gumataotao Rios|Rios]] || [[Timothy Geithner|Geithner]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2013\n| Rios || [[Jack Lew|Lew]] || Green\n|-\n|Federal Reserve Note\n| 2017\n| [[Jovita Carranza|Carranza]] || [[Steven T. Mnuchin|Mnuchin]] || Green\n|-\n|Federal Reserve Note\n| 2017A\n| Carranza || Mnuchin || Green\n|}\n\n==Obverse of current $1 bill==\n[[File:USDeptOfTreasurySeal-2003Bill.jpg|thumb|right|125px|Detail of the [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Seal]] as it appears on a $1 bill]]\n[[File:United States one dollar bill, fed seal L.jpg|thumb|left|75px|Example [[Federal Reserve Bank]] Seal (for [[Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco|San Francisco]]) as it appears on a $1 bill; the number ''12'' appears four times to confirm]]\n[[File:Comparison between Athenaeum Portrait and United States one-dollar bill.jpg|thumb|250px|Comparison between [[Gilbert Stuart]]'s 1796 ''[[Athenaeum Portrait]]'' and the image on the obverse of the bill. The image from the dollar bill above shows the subject flipped horizontally for ease of comparison.]]\nThe portrait of George Washington is displayed in the center of the [[Obverse and reverse|obverse]] of the one-dollar bill, as it has been since the 1869 design. The oval containing George Washington is propped up by bunches of bay laurel leaves.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nTo the left of George Washington is the Federal Reserve District seal. The name of the Federal Reserve Bank that issued the note encircles a capital letter (A\u2013L), identifying it among the twelve [[Federal Reserve Bank]]s. The sequential number of the bank (1: A, 2: B, etc.) is also displayed in the four corners of the open space on the bill. Until the redesign of the higher denominations of currency beginning in 1996, this seal was found on all denominations of Federal Reserve notes. Since then it is only present on the $1 and $2 notes, with the higher denominations only displaying a universal [[Federal Reserve System]] seal, and the bank letter and number beneath the upper left serial number.\n\nTo the right of George Washington is the [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department seal]]\nThe scales represent justice. The chevron with thirteen stars represents the original thirteen colonies. The key below the chevron represents authority and trust; 1789 is the year that the Department of the Treasury was established. The series 1969 dollar bills were the first to use a simplified Treasury seal, with the wording in [[English language|English]] instead of [[Latin]].\n\nBelow the FRB seal (to the left of George Washington) is the signature of the [[Treasurer of the United States]], and below the USDT Seal (right side) is the [[Secretary of the Treasury]]'s signature. To the left of the Secretary's signature is the [[Series (United States currency)|series]] date. A new series date, or addition or change of a sequential letter under a date, results from a change in the Secretary of the Treasury, the Treasurer of the United States, and/or a change to the note's appearance such as a new currency design.\n\nOn the edges are olive branches entwined around the 1s.  A small plate serial number-letter combination is on the lower right, and a small plate position (check) letter is on the upper left corner of the note. If \"FW\" appears before the lower right plate number it indicates that the bill was produced at the satellite [[Bureau of Engraving and Printing]] facility in [[Fort Worth]], [[Texas]]. Currency has been printed here since Series 1988A. No \"FW\" means the bill was made at the main plant in [[Washington, D.C.]].\n\n==Reverse of current $1 bill==\n\n[[File:1935 Dollar Bill Back Early Design.jpg|thumb|250px|right|President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Roosevelt]]'s conditional approval of the one-dollar bill's design in 1935, requiring that the appearance of the sides of the [[Great Seal of the United States|Great Seal]] be reversed, and together, captioned.]]\nThe reverse of the one-dollar bill has an ornate design that incorporates both sides of the [[Great Seal of the United States]] to the left and right of the word ''ONE''. This word appears prominently in the white space at the center of the bill in a capitalized, shadowed, and [[serif]]fed typeface. A smaller image of the word \"ONE\" is superimposed over the numeral \"1\" in each of the four corners of the bill.\n\n\"THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA\" spans the top of the bill, \"ONE DOLLAR\" is emblazoned along the bottom, and above the central \"ONE\" are the words \"[[In God We Trust|IN GOD WE TRUST]],\" which became the official [[motto]] of the United States in 1956 by an [[Act of Congress]]. Below the reverse of the Great Seal on the left side of the bill are the words \"THE GREAT SEAL,\" and below the obverse on the right side are the words \"OF THE UNITED STATES.\"\n\nThe Great Seal, originally designed in 1782 and added to the dollar bill's design in 1935, is surrounded by an elaborate floral design. The renderings used were the typical official government versions used since the 1880s.\n\nThe reverse of the seal on the left features a barren landscape dominated by an unfinished pyramid of 13 steps, topped by the [[Eye of Providence]] within a triangle. At the base of the pyramid are engraved the Roman numerals MDCCLXXVI (1776), the date of [[American Revolution|American independence]] from [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. At the top of the seal stands a Latin phrase, \"[[Annuit c\u0153ptis|ANNUIT COEPTIS]],\" meaning \"He favors our undertaking.\" At the bottom of the seal is a semicircular banner proclaiming \"[[Novus ordo seclorum|NOVUS ORDO SECLORUM]]\" meaning \"New Order of the Ages\" that is a reference to the new American era. To the left of this seal, a string of 13 pearls extends toward the edge of the bill.\n\nThe obverse of the seal on the right features a [[bald eagle]], the [[List of national birds|national bird]] and symbol of the United States. Above the [[Eagle (heraldry)|eagle]] is a radiant cluster of 13 stars arranged in a [[six-pointed star]]. The eagle's breast is covered by a [[heraldry|heraldic]] shield with 13 stripes that resemble those on the [[American flag]]. As on the first US flag, the stars and stripes stand for the 13 original states of the union. The eagle holds a ribbon in its beak reading \"[[E pluribus unum|E PLURIBUS UNUM]]\", a Latin phrase meaning \"Out of many [states], one [nation]\", a ''de facto'' motto of the United States (and the only one until 1956).  Both the phrases \"E Pluribus Unum\" and \"Annuit coeptis\" contain 13 letters. In its left talons the eagle holds 13 arrows, and in its right talons it holds an [[olive branch]] with 13 leaves and 13 olives, representing, respectively, the powers of war and peace. To the right of this seal, a string of 13 pearls extends toward the edge of the bill.  A plate position (check) number is normally found to the left of the eagle.\n\n== Collecting Federal Reserve dollar bills ==\nExcept for significant errors, and series 1988A web notes printed in small batches for some of the Federal Reserve districts (those from others are more common), green seal dollars are of little collector value.  However, two notes have generated public interest, although neither is scarce.\n\nIn 1963 dollar bills were produced for the Eleventh Federal Reserve District, headquartered in Dallas.  Since the FRD jurisdictions are sequentially numbered, notes received the corresponding letter \"K\", for the 11th letter of the alphabet. Some people noticed that the 1963 Dallas note, with the number \"11\" and a \"K\" surrounded by a black seal, appeared about the time President [[John F. Kennedy]] was shot in Dallas in November 1963.  The bill was not a commemorative issue and there was no connection between it and the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wndu.com/home/headlines/Kennedy-bills-have-eerie-connection-with-his-assassination-233045691.html|title=Kennedy bills have eerie connection with his assassination|first=NewsCenter16|last=Staff|website=WNDU.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968\u201369 [[Joseph W. Barr]] was Secretary of the Treasury for only 31 days and his signature appeared solely on the 1963B dollar bill.  Some collectors thought that his brief tenure might make these notes valuable, but use of their plates continued for some time after his term in office and 458,880,000 were printed.  Thus they are very common.<ref>[https://www.papermoneyauction.com/rare-or-not-rare-the-1963-b-1-dollar-barr-note Rare or Not Rare: The 1963-B $1 Dollar Barr Note]</ref>\n\nDollar Bills with interesting serial numbers can also be collected. One example of this is radar or \u201cpalindrome\u201c notes, where the numbers in the serial number are the same if you read from left to right or right to left. Very low serial numbers, or a long block of the same or repeating digits may also be of interest to specialists.  Another example is replacement notes, which have a star to the right of the serial number. The star designates that there was a printing error on one or more of the bills, and it has been replaced by one from a run specifically printed and numbered to be replacements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.howstuffworks.com/why-do-some-us-bills-have-a-star-instead-of-a-letter-at-the-end-of-the-serial-number.htm|title=Why do some U.S. bills have a star instead of a letter at the end of the serial number?|website=www.howstuffworks.com|access-date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>  Star notes may have some additional value depending on their condition, their year series or if they have an unusual serial number sequence.  To determine the rarity of modern star notes, production tables are maintained.<ref>[http://www.mycurrencycollection.com/reference/star-notes/1 $1 Star Note Tables]</ref>\n\n== Prosecution for the possession of a $1 bill ==\nIn Turkey the possession of a one-dollar bill can lead to a prosecution and sentence for terror related charges because it is seen as evidence for being a member of the [[G\u00fclen movement|G\u00fclen Movement]] founded by [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]], which is seen as a terror organization in Turkey. Turkish authorities believe that G\u00fclen used to present a one dollar bill to his followers and that they showed it to one another in order to make them recognizable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonpress.com/news/nasa-scientist-remains-trapped-in-turkish-prison-9645564|title=Over a Single Dollar Bill, a NASA Scientist Remains Trapped in a Turkish Prison|last=Wray|first=Dianna|date=2017-08-01|website=Houston Press|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nordicmonitor.com/2019/02/turkeys-war-against-one-dollar-us-bill-deemed-as-evidence-of-crime/|title=Turkey\u2019s war on the US one dollar bill to justify persecution of its critics|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/03/25/how-did-a-nasa-scientist-get-in-turkish-prison|title=How Did a NASA Scientist Get in Turkish Prison?|last=Snell|first=Lindsey|date=2017-03-25|access-date=2019-03-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Redesign or replacement of the dollar bill ==\n[[File:Figure 2 Estimated Cumulative Present-Value Net Loss to the Government from Actively and Gradually Replacing $1 Notes with $1 Coins over 30 Years (46756288014).jpg|thumb|[[Government Accountability Office|GAO]] estimated 30-year present-value cost of replacing $1 notes with $1 coins]]\n{{see also|Dollar coin (United States)#Popularity}}\n\nIn modern times, the one dollar bill is used much more than the [[Dollar coin (United States)|dollar coin]], despite the U.S. Government's repeated efforts to promote the latter.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=CNN Money | url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/04/27/pf/new_dollar/ | title=Congress tries again for a dollar coin | first=Gordon T. | last=Anderson | date=April 25, 2005 | access-date=June 26, 2012}}</ref> There are organizations specifically aimed at either preventing ([[Save the Greenback]])<ref>\"Is U.S. Ready to See the Dollar Bill Pass?\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' June 12, 1995; p. 4</ref> or advocating ([[Coin Coalition]])<ref>Barro, Robert J. and Stevenson, Betsey: [http://home.manhattan.edu/~fiona.maclachlan/mb/coin.htm Do You Want That In Paper, or Metal?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041231164455/http://home.manhattan.edu/~fiona.maclachlan/mb/coin.htm |date=2004-12-31 }}, ''Wall Street Journal'', November 6, 1997</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2002/04/11/pf/q_pennies/|title=Should the penny go? - Apr. 11, 2002|publisher=CNN|access-date=}}</ref> the complete elimination of the one-dollar bill in favor of the dollar coin.\n\nOn November 29, 2012, a [[United States House of Representatives|House]] subcommittee met to consider replacing the dollar bill. This action took place after the seventh [[Government Accountability Office]] report on the subject. The latest report claimed that switching to dollar coins would save $4.4 billion over thirty years. However, according to polls, few Americans want to give up dollar bills.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ax-dollar-bills-save-money-congress-article-1.1211013|title=Congress considers getting rid of dollar bills for $1 coins to save money|last1=Straw|first1=Joseph|last2=Lysiak|first2=Matthew|last3=Murray|first3=Rheana|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 30, 2012|access-date=January 7, 2013}}</ref> Recent budgets passed by Congress have included provisions to prevent the Treasury Department from spending any of its funds to redesign the one-dollar bill, largely because of potential cost impacts on the vending machine industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/2014/01/28/one-is-loneliest-dollar-bill|title=One Is the Loneliest Dollar Bill|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics|United States}}\n* [[Sherman Silver Purchase Act]]\n* [[Where's George?]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* Official 2006 ''Blackbook Price Guide to United States Paper Money'' (38th edition)\n* ''Standard Catalog of United States Paper Money'' 17th edition published by Krause Publications\n* The Official RED BOOK A Guide Book of United States Paper Money\n* Standard Guide to Small-Size U.S. Paper Money\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://s3.imagediver.org/topic/album/4294b0e/one_dollar_bill_5/1/index.html The One Dollar Bill, Zoomable and Annotated]\n* [https://uscurrency.gov/security/1-security-features-1963-present High-Res Federal Reserve $1 Note]\n\n{{US currency and coinage}}\n{{George Washington}}\n{{Gilbert Stuart}}\n\n[[Category:1862 introductions]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to George Washington in the United States]]\n[[Category:Banknotes of the United States|*001]]\n[[Category:One-base-unit banknotes]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the U.S. one-dollar coin|United States dollar coin}}\n{{morefootnotes|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox banknote\n| denomination        = One [[United States dollar|dollar]]\n| country             = United States\n| value               = $1\n| width_mm            = 6.14 inches \u2248 156.1\n| height_mm           = 2.61 inches \u2248 66.3\n| thickness_mm        = 0.109\n| weight_g            = Approx. 1<ref>{{cite web|author1=U.S. Currency Education Program|title=Weight of a US Banknote|url=https://www.uscurrency.gov/content/weight-banknote|website=uscurrency.gov|publisher=US Federal Reserve|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>\n| paper_type          = 75% cotton<br />25% linen<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uscurrency.gov/history-american-currency|title=The History of American Currency - U.S. Currency Education Program|publisher=}}</ref>\n| years_of_printing   = 1929 \u2013 present (Small size)\n| obverse             = US one dollar bill, obverse, series 2009.jpg\n| adsaffs Design      = [[George Washington]]\n| obverse_design    = [[George Washington]]\n| obverse_design_date = 1963\n| reverse             = US one dollar bill, reverse, series 2009.jpg\n| reverse_design      = [[Great Seal of the United States]]\n| reverse_designer    =\n| reverse_design_date = 1935\n}}\nThe '''United States one-dollar bill''' ($1) since 1876 has been the lowest value [[Denomination (currency)|denomination]] of [[United States dollar|United States paper currency]]. An image of the first [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] (1789\u20131797), [[George Washington]], based on the ''[[Athenaeum Portrait]]'', a 1796 painting by [[Gilbert Stuart]], is currently featured on the [[obverse]], and the [[Great Seal of the United States]] is featured on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]]. The one-dollar bill has the oldest overall design of all U.S. currency currently being produced (The current [[United States two-dollar bill|two-dollar bill]] obverse design dates from 1928, while the reverse appeared in 1976). The obverse design of the dollar bill seen today debuted in 1963 (the reverse in 1935) when it was first issued as a [[Federal Reserve Note]] (previously, one dollar bills were [[Silver certificate (United States)|Silver Certificates]]).\n\nThe inclusion of the motto, \"[[In God We Trust]],\" on all currency was required by law in 1955, and first appeared on [[Banknote|paper money]] in 1957.\n\nThe [[Federal Reserve]] says the average life of a $1 bill in [[Circulation_(currency)|circulation]] is 5.8 years before it is replaced because of wear.<ref>{{cite web| publisher = Federal Reserve|title=How long is the life span of U.S. paper money?|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/faqs/how-long-is-the-life-span-of-us-paper-money.htm}}</ref> Approximately 42% of all U.S. currency produced in 2009 were one-dollar bills.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Bureau of Engraving and Printing|title=1$ Note|url=http://www.moneyfactory.gov/small1denom.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216014938/http://www.moneyfactory.gov/small1denom.html|archivedate=2013-02-16}}</ref>\nAs of 2017, there were 12.1 billion one-dollar bills in circulation worldwide <ref>https://monstertubenetwork.com/hidden-facts-that-will-surprise-you-about-the-one-dollar-bill/</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Large size notes===\n\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1862-Fr-16c.jpg|thumb|250px|left|First $1 bill issued in 1862 as a Legal Tender Note]]\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1880-Fr-29.jpg|thumb|250px|Series 1880 $1 [[United States Note|Legal Tender]]]]\n[[File:US-$1-SC-1886-Fr-217.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Series of 1886 $1 Silver Certificate featuring [[Martha Washington]]]]\n[[File:US-$1-SC-1896-Fr-224-(3923429).jpg|thumb|250px|Famous 1896 \"[[Educational Series]]\" $1 Silver Certificate]]\n''({{small|approximately}} 7\u215c \u00d7 3\u215b in \u2245 187 \u00d7 79 &nbsp;mm)''\n* '''1862''': The first one-dollar bill was issued as a Legal Tender Note ([[United States Note]]) with a portrait of [[Salmon P. Chase]], the [[Secretary of the Treasury]] under President [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Tulane University|title=Salmon P. Chase|url=http://www.tulane.edu/~latner/Chase.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231131605/http://www.tulane.edu/~latner/Chase.html|archivedate=2006-12-31}}</ref><ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p56</ref>\n* '''1869''': The $1 United States Note was redesigned with a portrait of [[George Washington]] in the center and a [[Vignetting|vignette]] of [[Christopher Columbus]] sighting land to the left. The obverse of the note also featured overprinting of the word ONE numerous times in very small green type and blue tinting of the paper. Although this note is technically a United States Note, {{sc|TREASURY NOTE}} appeared on it instead of {{sc|UNITED STATES NOTE}}.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p57</ref>\n* '''1874''': The Series of 1869 United States Note was revised. Changes on the obverse included removing the green and blue tinting, adding a red floral design around the word {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}}, and changing the term {{sc|TREASURY NOTE}} to {{sc|UNITED STATES NOTE}}. The reverse was completely redesigned. This note was also issued as Series of 1875 and 1878.<ref name=\"GuideBook\">A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p58</ref>\n* '''1880''': The red floral design around the words {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}} and {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}} on the United States Note was removed and replaced with a large red seal. Later versions also had blue serial numbers and a small seal moved to the left side of the note.<ref name=\"GuideBook\" />\n* '''1886''': The first woman to appear on U.S. currency, [[Martha Washington]], was featured on the $1 [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificate]]. The reverse of the note featured an ornate design that occupied the entire note, excluding the borders.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p61</ref>\n* '''1890''': One-dollar Treasury or \"Coin Notes\" were issued for government purchases of silver bullion from the silver mining industry. The reverse featured the large word {{sc|ONE}} in the center surrounded by an ornate design that occupied almost the entire note.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 65</ref>\n* '''1891''': The reverse of the Series of 1890 Treasury Note was redesigned because the treasury felt that it was too \"busy,\" which would make it too easy to counterfeit. More open space was incorporated into the new design. The obverse was largely unchanged.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 66</ref>\n* '''1896''': The famous \"[[Educational Series]]\" Silver Certificate was issued. The entire obverse was covered with artwork of [[Allegory|allegorical]] figures representing \"history instructing youth\" in front of [[Washington D.C.]] The reverse featured portraits of George and Martha Washington surrounded by an ornate design that occupied almost the entire note.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 62\u201363</ref>\n* '''1899''': The $1 Silver Certificate was again redesigned. The obverse featured a vignette of the [[United States Capitol]] behind a [[bald eagle]] perched on an [[Flag of the United States|American flag]]. Below that were small portraits of [[Abraham Lincoln]] to the left and [[Ulysses S. Grant]] to the right.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 63</ref>\n* '''1917''': The obverse of the $1 United States Note was changed slightly with the removal of ornamental frames that surrounded the serial numbers.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 59</ref>\n* '''1918''': The only large-sized, Federal Reserve Note-like $1 bill was issued as a [[Federal Reserve Bank Note]] (not to be confused with [[Federal Reserve Note]]s). Each note was an obligation of the issuing Federal Reserve Bank and could only be redeemed at that corresponding bank. The obverse of the note featured a borderless portrait of George Washington to the left and wording in the entire center. The reverse featured a bald eagle in flight clutching an [[American flag]].<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 66\u201367</ref>\n* '''1923''': Both the one-dollar [[United States Note]] and Silver Certificate were redesigned. Both notes featured the same reverse and an almost identical obverse with the same border design and portrait of George Washington. The only difference between the two notes was the color of ink used for the numeral 1 crossed by the word {{sc|DOLLAR}}, [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury seal]], and serial numbers along with the wording of the obligations. These dollar bills were the first and only large-size notes with a standardized design for different types of notes of the same denomination; this same concept would later be used on small-size notes.<ref>A Guide Book of United States Paper Money (Whitman) p 59, 64</ref>\n\n===Small size notes===\n[[File:First Small Size Silver Certificate (face, 1928).jpg|thumb|250px|The first small-size $1 Silver Certificate.]]\n[[File:US $1 1928 Silver Certificate reverse.jpg|thumb|250px|Common reverse of $1 Silver Certificates (Series of 1928-1934) and $1 United States Notes ([[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]]), commonly referred to as \"Funnybacks\"]]\n[[File:US-$1-LT-1928-Fr.1500.jpg|thumb|250px|The first small-size $1 United States Banknote printed.]]\n''(6.14 length \u00d7 2.61 width\u00d7 0.0043 in thickness  = 156 \u00d7 66.3 \u00d7 0.11&nbsp;mm)''\n\nIn 1928, all currency was changed to the size which is familiar today. The first one-dollar bills were issued as [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificates]] under [[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]]. The Treasury seal and serial numbers were dark blue. The obverse was nearly identical to the Series of 1923 $1 silver certificate, but the Treasury seal featured spikes around it and a large gray {{sc|ONE}} replaced the blue \"{{small|1 DOLLAR}}.\" The reverse, too, had the same border design as the Series of 1923 $1 bill, but the center featured a large ornate {{sc|ONE}} superimposed by {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}}. These are commonly known as \"Funnybacks\" due to the rather odd-looking \"ONE\" on the reverse. These $1 silver certificates were issued until 1934.\n\nIn 1933, [[Series of 1928 (United States Currency)|Series of 1928]] $1 [[United States Note]]s were issued to supplement the supply of $1 Silver Certificates. Its Treasury seal and serial numbers were red and there was different wording on the obverse of the note. However, a month after their production, it was realized that there would be no real need for these notes and production was stopped. A small number of these $1 bills entered circulation and the rest were kept in Treasury vaults until 1949 when they were issued in [[Puerto Rico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcurrencyvalues.com/1928_one_dollar_red_seal/|title=Series of 1928 One Dollar Red Seal United States Note \u2013 Values and Pricing - Sell Old Currency|website=OldCurrencyValues.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1934, the design of the $1 silver certificate was changed.  This occurred with that year's passage of the Silver Purchase Act, which led to a large increase in dollar bills backed by that metal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://encyclopedia-of-money.blogspot.com/2012/05/silver-purchase-act-of-1934-united.html|title=Encyclopedia of Money: Silver Purchase Act of 1934 (United States)|website=encyclopedia-of-money.Blogspot.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>  Under Washington's portrait, {{sc|ONE SILVER DOLLAR}} was changed to {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}}. The Treasury seal was moved to the right and superimposed over {{sc|ONE}}, and a blue numeral 1 was added to the left. The reverse remained the same.\n\nA year later, in 1935, the design of the one-dollar bill was changed again. On the obverse, the blue numeral 1 was changed to gray and made smaller, the gray {{sc|ONE}} to the right was removed, the Treasury seal was made smaller and superimposed by {{sc|WASHINGTON D.C.}}, and a stylized {{sc|ONE DOLLAR}} was added over the treasury seal. The reverse was also changed to its current design, except for the absence of {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}.\n\n[[File:US $1 1935A North Africa Silver Certificate.jpg|thumb|250px|Special issue $1 Silver Certificate for Allied troops in North Africa]]\n\n[[World War II]] brought about [[Hawaii overprint note|special issues of one-dollar bills in 1942.]]\nSpecial $1 Silver Certificates were issued for [[Hawaii]] in case of a Japanese invasion. {{sc|HAWAII}} was printed vertically on the left and right side of the obverse and also horizontally across the reverse. The seal and serial numbers were changed to brown. Special Silver Certificates were also issued as payment for Allied troops in North Africa about to begin their assault into Europe. The only difference on these one-dollar bills was a yellow instead of blue seal. Both of these types of notes could be declared worthless if they fell into enemy hands.\n\nThe next change came in 1957 when the $1 bill became the first piece of paper U.S. currency to bear the motto {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}; it was added over the word {{sc|ONE}} on the reverse. Initially the [[Bureau of Engraving and Printing|BEP]] began printing the motto on notes printed with the new 32 note press, but soon Series of 1935G bills printed on an 18 note press featured the motto.\n\nThe final production of $1 Silver Certificates occurred in late 1963. In 1964, the redemption of Silver Certificates for silver coin ended and in 1968 the redemption of Silver Certificates for silver bullion ended.\n\nProduction of one-dollar [[Federal Reserve Note]]s was undertaken in late 1963 to replace the soon-to-be obsolete $1 Silver Certificate. The design on the reverse remained the same, but the border design on the obverse underwent considerable modification, as the mostly abstract filigrees were replaced with designs that were mostly botanical in nature. In addition, the word \"one,\" which appeared eight times around the border in small type, was eliminated.  The serial numbers and treasury seal were printed in green ink. This was the first time the one-dollar bill was printed as a Federal Reserve Note.\n\nThe first change since then came in 1969, when the $1 was among all denominations of Federal Reserve Notes to feature the new [[Symbols of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury seal]], with English wording instead of Latin.<ref>http://www.onedollarbill.org/history.html</ref>\n\nThe $1 bill became the first denomination printed at the new Western Currency Facility in February 1991, when a shipment of 3.2 million [[Replacement banknote|star notes]] from the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas|Dallas FRB]] was produced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uspapermoney.info/groups/f1988as.txt |title=data|website=uspapermoney.info}}</ref>\n\nThough bill denominations of $5 and higher have been redesigned twice since 1995 as part of ongoing anti-counterfeiting efforts, there are currently no plans to redesign the $1 or $2 bills.\n\n====Experimental issues====\n{{Main|Web notes}}\nSince 1933, the one-dollar bill has been the exclusive experimental denomination among circulating US currency (except for the Natick experiment in 1981, see below). The first experiment was conducted in January and February of that year to assess the effects of using different ratios of cotton to linen in the make-up of the bills. Series 1928A and 1928B $1 silver certificates with serial number block letters X-B and Y-B were used as the experimental group; the Z-B block was used as the control group. The results of the experiment were inconclusive.\n\nIn 1937, another test was conducted, similar in style to the 1933 experiment. This test used Series 1935 one-dollar bills. The particular notes used in this experiment can be identified by their serial numbers. Notes ranging from A00000001B to A06180000B and B00000001B\u2013B03300000B were the experimental group and notes ranging from C00000001B to C03300000B were part of the control group. No conclusive results were found.\n\nA better known test was done in 1942 during World War II to test alternative types of paper. This was a precautionary measure in case the current type of paper supply could not be maintained. Series 1935A notes made of the special paper and were printed with a red \"S\" to the right of the treasury seal, while notes of the control group were printed with a red ''R''. Because they have some collector value, fake red S's and R's have been applied to regular Series 1935A notes to try to pass them at a higher value; checking a note's serial numbers can prevent this. Serial numbers of the R group range from S70884001C to S72068000C and serial numbers of the S group range from S73884001C to S75068000C.\n\nSometime in the early to mid-1960s, the BEP experimented with a new firm, the Gilbert Paper Company, to see if they could duplicate the usual paper production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coinbooks.org/esylum_v15n22a21.html|title=THE GILBERT PAPER CO $1 FEDERAL RESERVE NOTES, SERIES 1963|website=www.CoinBooks.org|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref> The BEP selected a series of notes printed by the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia|Philadelphia FRB]] as the test subjects. Serial numbers for this group range from C60800001A to C61440000A.\n\nIn August 1981, a similar experiment occurred during production of Series 1977A, when the BEP printed a few print runs on Natick paper. They included a regular run and a star note run from the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond|Richmond FRB]], with serial numbers ranging from E76800001H through E80640000H and E07052001* through E07680000* (note that many sources incorrectly identify the star range as Philadelphia instead of Richmond). One print run of $10 star notes, also from Richmond, was included in this paper test, making it so far the only experimental printing not exclusive to the $1.\n\nOne-dollar bills were again the subject of experimentation in May 1992, when the BEP began to test a [[Offset printing#Web-fed litho|web-fed]] [[Intaglio (printmaking)|Intaglio]] printing press. Because of a need for greater quantities of $1 FRNs, the BEP sent out REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS (RFP) (year 1985) NO. BEP-85-73 to procure a web-fed intaglio printing press to dramatically increase the production of currency notes within the confines of their current (1985) 14th & C street facility. Instead of printing one side of a square sheet of 32 notes at a time, the web-fed press used 96 engraved images or plate-cylinder to print the back of the note, then another 96 image engraved plate-cylinder to print the front of the note. Both sides of notes were printed from a continuous roll of paper. The Alexander-Hamilton intaglio Web press printed both sides of intaglio at the same time. The web-press was designed as a full-blown production press as opposed to an experimental press. The notes were issued in Series 1988A, 1993, and 1995. Because of mechanical problems and operator error, as well as the sometimes poor quality of the notes, production was ended in July 1996. Web notes can be identified by the back plate number next to {{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}} and the removal of face check letters and quadrant numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspapermoney.info/general/webs.html|title=USPaperMoney.Info: Web Notes|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Series dates===\n\n====Small size====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Type\n! Series\n! [[Treasurer of the United States|Treasurer]]\n! [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary]]\n! [[Symbols of the United States Department of the Treasury|Seal]]\n|-\n| [[Legal Tender Note]]\n| 1928\n| [[W. O. Woods|Woods]] || [[William H. Woodin|Woodin]] || Red\n|-\n| [[Silver Certificate]]\n| 1928\n| [[Harold Theodore Tate|Tate]] || [[Andrew Mellon|Mellon]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928A\n| Woods || Mellon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928B\n| Woods || [[Ogden L. Mills|Mills]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928C\n| Woods || Woodin || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928D\n| [[William Alexander Julian|Julian]] || Woodin || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1928E\n| Julian || [[Henry Morgenthau, Jr.|Morgenthau]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1934\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A Hawaii\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Brown\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935A North Africa\n| Julian || Morgenthau || Yellow\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935B\n| Julian || [[Fred M. Vinson|Vinson]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935C\n| Julian || [[John Wesley Snyder (US Cabinet Secretary)|Snyder]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935D\n| [[Georgia Neese Clark|Clark]] || Snyder || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935E\n| [[Ivy Baker Priest|Priest]] || [[George M. Humphrey|Humphrey]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935F\n| Priest || [[Robert B. Anderson|Anderson]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935G\n| [[Elizabeth Rudel Smith|Smith]] || [[C. Douglas Dillon|Dillon]] || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935G Motto\n| Smith || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1935H\n| Granahan || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957\n| Priest || Anderson || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957A\n| Smith || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n| Silver Certificate\n| 1957B\n| Granahan || Dillon || Blue\n|-\n|[[Federal Reserve Note]]\n| 1963\n| Smith || Dillon || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1963A\n| Granahan || [[Henry H. Fowler|Fowler]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1963B\n| Granahan || [[Joseph W. Barr|Barr]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969\n| [[Dorothy Andrews Elston Kabis|Elston]] || [[David M. Kennedy|Kennedy]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969A\n| [[Dorothy Andrews Elston Kabis|Kabis]] || Kennedy || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969B\n| Kabis || [[John Connally|Connally]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969C\n| [[Romana Acosta Ba\u00f1uelos|Ba\u00f1uelos]] || Connally || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1969D\n| Ba\u00f1uelos || [[George Shultz|Shultz]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1974\n| [[Francine Irving Neff|Neff]] || [[William E. Simon|Simon]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1977\n| [[Azie Taylor Morton|Morton]] || [[W. Michael Blumenthal|Blumenthal]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1977A\n| Morton || [[G. William Miller|Miller]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1981\n| [[Angela Marie Buchanan|Buchanan]] || [[Donald Regan|Regan]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1981A\n| [[Katherine D. Ortega|Ortega]] || Regan || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1985\n| Ortega || [[James Baker|Baker]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1988\n| Ortega || [[Nicholas F. Brady|Brady]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1988A\n| [[Catalina Vasquez Villalpando|Villalpando]] || Brady || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1993\n| [[Mary Ellen Withrow|Withrow]] || [[Lloyd Bentsen|Bentsen]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1995\n| Withrow || [[Robert E. Rubin|Rubin]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 1999\n| Withrow || [[Lawrence Summers|Summers]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2001\n| [[Rosario Marin|Marin]] || [[Paul H. O'Neill|O'Neill]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2003\n| Marin || [[John W. Snow|Snow]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2003A\n| [[Anna Escobedo Cabral|Cabral]] || Snow || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2006\n| Cabral || [[Henry Paulson|Paulson]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2009\n| [[Rosa Gumataotao Rios|Rios]] || [[Timothy Geithner|Geithner]] || Green\n|-\n| Federal Reserve Note\n| 2013\n| Rios || [[Jack Lew|Lew]] || Green\n|-\n|Federal Reserve Note\n| 2017\n| [[Jovita Carranza|Carranza]] || [[Steven T. Mnuchin|Mnuchin]] || Green\n|-\n|Federal Reserve Note\n| 2017A\n| Carranza || Mnuchin || Green\n|}\n\n==Obverse of current $1 bill==\n[[File:USDeptOfTreasurySeal-2003Bill.jpg|thumb|right|125px|Detail of the [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Seal]] as it appears on a $1 bill]]\n[[File:United States one dollar bill, fed seal L.jpg|thumb|left|75px|Example [[Federal Reserve Bank]] Seal (for [[Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco|San Francisco]]) as it appears on a $1 bill; the number ''12'' appears four times to confirm]]\n[[File:Comparison between Athenaeum Portrait and United States one-dollar bill.jpg|thumb|250px|Comparison between [[Gilbert Stuart]]'s 1796 ''[[Athenaeum Portrait]]'' and the image on the obverse of the bill. The image from the dollar bill above shows the subject flipped horizontally for ease of comparison.]]\nThe portrait of George Washington is displayed in the center of the [[Obverse and reverse|obverse]] of the one-dollar bill, as it has been since the 1869 design. The oval containing George Washington is propped up by bunches of bay laurel leaves.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}\n\nTo the left of George Washington is the Federal Reserve District seal. The name of the Federal Reserve Bank that issued the note encircles a capital letter (A\u2013L), identifying it among the twelve [[Federal Reserve Bank]]s. The sequential number of the bank (1: A, 2: B, etc.) is also displayed in the four corners of the open space on the bill. Until the redesign of the higher denominations of currency beginning in 1996, this seal was found on all denominations of Federal Reserve notes. Since then it is only present on the $1 and $2 notes, with the higher denominations only displaying a universal [[Federal Reserve System]] seal, and the bank letter and number beneath the upper left serial number.\n\nTo the right of George Washington is the [[Seal of the United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department seal]]\nThe scales represent justice. The chevron with thirteen stars represents the original thirteen colonies. The key below the chevron represents authority and trust; 1789 is the year that the Department of the Treasury was established. The series 1969 dollar bills were the first to use a simplified Treasury seal, with the wording in [[English language|English]] instead of [[Latin]].\n\nBelow the FRB seal (to the left of George Washington) is the signature of the [[Treasurer of the United States]], and below the USDT Seal (right side) is the [[Secretary of the Treasury]]'s signature. To the left of the Secretary's signature is the [[Series (United States currency)|series]] date. A new series date, or addition or change of a sequential letter under a date, results from a change in the Secretary of the Treasury, the Treasurer of the United States, and/or a change to the note's appearance such as a new currency design.\n\nOn the edges are olive branches entwined around the 1s.  A small plate serial number-letter combination is on the lower right, and a small plate position (check) letter is on the upper left corner of the note. If \"FW\" appears before the lower right plate number it indicates that the bill was produced at the satellite [[Bureau of Engraving and Printing]] facility in [[Fort Worth]], [[Texas]]. Currency has been printed here since Series 1988A. No \"FW\" means the bill was made at the main plant in [[Washington, D.C.]].\n\n==Reverse of current $1 bill==\n\n[[File:1935 Dollar Bill Back Early Design.jpg|thumb|250px|right|President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Roosevelt]]'s conditional approval of the one-dollar bill's design in 1935, requiring that the appearance of the sides of the [[Great Seal of the United States|Great Seal]] be reversed, and together, captioned.]]\nThe reverse of the one-dollar bill has an ornate design that incorporates both sides of the [[Great Seal of the United States]] to the left and right of the word ''ONE''. This word appears prominently in the white space at the center of the bill in a capitalized, shadowed, and [[serif]]fed typeface. A smaller image of the word \"ONE\" is superimposed over the numeral \"1\" in each of the four corners of the bill.\n\n\"THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA\" spans the top of the bill, \"ONE DOLLAR\" is emblazoned along the bottom, and above the central \"ONE\" are the words \"[[In God We Trust|IN GOD WE TRUST]],\" which became the official [[motto]] of the United States in 1956 by an [[Act of Congress]]. Below the reverse of the Great Seal on the left side of the bill are the words \"THE GREAT SEAL,\" and below the obverse on the right side are the words \"OF THE UNITED STATES.\"\n\nThe Great Seal, originally designed in 1782 and added to the dollar bill's design in 1935, is surrounded by an elaborate floral design. The renderings used were the typical official government versions used since the 1880s.\n\nThe reverse of the seal on the left features a barren landscape dominated by an unfinished pyramid of 13 steps, topped by the [[Eye of Providence]] within a triangle. At the base of the pyramid are engraved the Roman numerals MDCCLXXVI (1776), the date of [[American Revolution|American independence]] from [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. At the top of the seal stands a Latin phrase, \"[[Annuit c\u0153ptis|ANNUIT COEPTIS]],\" meaning \"He favors our undertaking.\" At the bottom of the seal is a semicircular banner proclaiming \"[[Novus ordo seclorum|NOVUS ORDO SECLORUM]]\" meaning \"New Order of the Ages\" that is a reference to the new American era. To the left of this seal, a string of 13 pearls extends toward the edge of the bill.\n\nThe obverse of the seal on the right features a [[bald eagle]], the [[List of national birds|national bird]] and symbol of the United States. Above the [[Eagle (heraldry)|eagle]] is a radiant cluster of 13 stars arranged in a [[six-pointed star]]. The eagle's breast is covered by a [[heraldry|heraldic]] shield with 13 stripes that resemble those on the [[American flag]]. As on the first US flag, the stars and stripes stand for the 13 original states of the union. The eagle holds a ribbon in its beak reading \"[[E pluribus unum|E PLURIBUS UNUM]]\", a Latin phrase meaning \"Out of many [states], one [nation]\", a ''de facto'' motto of the United States (and the only one until 1956).  Both the phrases \"E Pluribus Unum\" and \"Annuit coeptis\" contain 13 letters. In its left talons the eagle holds 13 arrows, and in its right talons it holds an [[olive branch]] with 13 leaves and 13 olives, representing, respectively, the powers of war and peace. To the right of this seal, a string of 13 pearls extends toward the edge of the bill.  A plate position (check) number is normally found to the left of the eagle.\n\n== Collecting Federal Reserve dollar bills ==\nExcept for significant errors, and series 1988A web notes printed in small batches for some of the Federal Reserve districts (those from others are more common), green seal dollars are of little collector value.  However, two notes have generated public interest, although neither is scarce.\n\nIn 1963 dollar bills were produced for the Eleventh Federal Reserve District, headquartered in Dallas.  Since the FRD jurisdictions are sequentially numbered, notes received the corresponding letter \"K\", for the 11th letter of the alphabet. Some people noticed that the 1963 Dallas note, with the number \"11\" and a \"K\" surrounded by a black seal, appeared about the time President [[John F. Kennedy]] was shot in Dallas in November 1963.  The bill was not a commemorative issue and there was no connection between it and the shooting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wndu.com/home/headlines/Kennedy-bills-have-eerie-connection-with-his-assassination-233045691.html|title=Kennedy bills have eerie connection with his assassination|first=NewsCenter16|last=Staff|website=WNDU.com|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968\u201369 [[Joseph W. Barr]] was Secretary of the Treasury for only 31 days and his signature appeared solely on the 1963B dollar bill.  Some collectors thought that his brief tenure might make these notes valuable, but use of their plates continued for some time after his term in office and 458,880,000 were printed.  Thus they are very common.<ref>[https://www.papermoneyauction.com/rare-or-not-rare-the-1963-b-1-dollar-barr-note Rare or Not Rare: The 1963-B $1 Dollar Barr Note]</ref>\n\nDollar Bills with interesting serial numbers can also be collected. One example of this is radar or \u201cpalindrome\u201c notes, where the numbers in the serial number are the same if you read from left to right or right to left. Very low serial numbers, or a long block of the same or repeating digits may also be of interest to specialists.  Another example is replacement notes, which have a star to the right of the serial number. The star designates that there was a printing error on one or more of the bills, and it has been replaced by one from a run specifically printed and numbered to be replacements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.howstuffworks.com/why-do-some-us-bills-have-a-star-instead-of-a-letter-at-the-end-of-the-serial-number.htm|title=Why do some U.S. bills have a star instead of a letter at the end of the serial number?|website=www.howstuffworks.com|access-date=May 22, 2019}}</ref>  Star notes may have some additional value depending on their condition, their year series or if they have an unusual serial number sequence.  To determine the rarity of modern star notes, production tables are maintained.<ref>[http://www.mycurrencycollection.com/reference/star-notes/1 $1 Star Note Tables]</ref>\n\n== Prosecution for the possession of a $1 bill ==\nIn Turkey the possession of a one-dollar bill can lead to a prosecution and sentence for terror related charges because it is seen as evidence for being a member of the [[G\u00fclen movement|G\u00fclen Movement]] founded by [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]], which is seen as a terror organization in Turkey. Turkish authorities believe that G\u00fclen used to present a one dollar bill to his followers and that they showed it to one another in order to make them recognizable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonpress.com/news/nasa-scientist-remains-trapped-in-turkish-prison-9645564|title=Over a Single Dollar Bill, a NASA Scientist Remains Trapped in a Turkish Prison|last=Wray|first=Dianna|date=2017-08-01|website=Houston Press|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nordicmonitor.com/2019/02/turkeys-war-against-one-dollar-us-bill-deemed-as-evidence-of-crime/|title=Turkey\u2019s war on the US one dollar bill to justify persecution of its critics|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/03/25/how-did-a-nasa-scientist-get-in-turkish-prison|title=How Did a NASA Scientist Get in Turkish Prison?|last=Snell|first=Lindsey|date=2017-03-25|access-date=2019-03-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Redesign or replacement of the dollar bill ==\n[[File:Figure 2 Estimated Cumulative Present-Value Net Loss to the Government from Actively and Gradually Replacing $1 Notes with $1 Coins over 30 Years (46756288014).jpg|thumb|[[Government Accountability Office|GAO]] estimated 30-year present-value cost of replacing $1 notes with $1 coins]]\n{{see also|Dollar coin (United States)#Popularity}}\n\nIn modern times, the one dollar bill is used much more than the [[Dollar coin (United States)|dollar coin]], despite the U.S. Government's repeated efforts to promote the latter.<ref>{{cite web | publisher=CNN Money | url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/04/27/pf/new_dollar/ | title=Congress tries again for a dollar coin | first=Gordon T. | last=Anderson | date=April 25, 2005 | access-date=June 26, 2012}}</ref> There are organizations specifically aimed at either preventing ([[Save the Greenback]])<ref>\"Is U.S. Ready to See the Dollar Bill Pass?\" ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' June 12, 1995; p. 4</ref> or advocating ([[Coin Coalition]])<ref>Barro, Robert J. and Stevenson, Betsey: [http://home.manhattan.edu/~fiona.maclachlan/mb/coin.htm Do You Want That In Paper, or Metal?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041231164455/http://home.manhattan.edu/~fiona.maclachlan/mb/coin.htm |date=2004-12-31 }}, ''Wall Street Journal'', November 6, 1997</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2002/04/11/pf/q_pennies/|title=Should the penny go? - Apr. 11, 2002|publisher=CNN|access-date=}}</ref> the complete elimination of the one-dollar bill in favor of the dollar coin.\n\nOn November 29, 2012, a [[United States House of Representatives|House]] subcommittee met to consider replacing the dollar bill. This action took place after the seventh [[Government Accountability Office]] report on the subject. The latest report claimed that switching to dollar coins would save $4.4 billion over thirty years. However, according to polls, few Americans want to give up dollar bills.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ax-dollar-bills-save-money-congress-article-1.1211013|title=Congress considers getting rid of dollar bills for $1 coins to save money|last1=Straw|first1=Joseph|last2=Lysiak|first2=Matthew|last3=Murray|first3=Rheana|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=November 30, 2012|access-date=January 7, 2013}}</ref> Recent budgets passed by Congress have included provisions to prevent the Treasury Department from spending any of its funds to redesign the one-dollar bill, largely because of potential cost impacts on the vending machine industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/2014/01/28/one-is-loneliest-dollar-bill|title=One Is the Loneliest Dollar Bill|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics|United States}}\n* [[Sherman Silver Purchase Act]]\n* [[Where's George?]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* Official 2006 ''Blackbook Price Guide to United States Paper Money'' (38th edition)\n* ''Standard Catalog of United States Paper Money'' 17th edition published by Krause Publications\n* The Official RED BOOK A Guide Book of United States Paper Money\n* Standard Guide to Small-Size U.S. Paper Money\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://s3.imagediver.org/topic/album/4294b0e/one_dollar_bill_5/1/index.html The One Dollar Bill, Zoomable and Annotated]\n* [https://uscurrency.gov/security/1-security-features-1963-present High-Res Federal Reserve $1 Note]\n\n{{US currency and coinage}}\n{{George Washington}}\n{{Gilbert Stuart}}\n\n[[Category:1862 introductions]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to George Washington in the United States]]\n[[Category:Banknotes of the United States|*001]]\n[[Category:One-base-unit banknotes]]\n", "name_user": "98.182.243.150", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLarge size notes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_one-dollar_bill"}
