ril 17, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Grumpy Cat's Worst Christmas Ever]]''\n| [[Grumpy Cat]]\n|Voice role\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[Addicted to Fresno]]''\n| Kelly\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Driftless Area]]''\n| Jean\n| \n|\n|-\n|rowspan=4|2016\n| ''[[Dirty Grandpa]]''\n| Lenore\n| \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Joshy (film)|Joshy]]''\n| Jen\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Pistol Shrimps]]''\n| Herself\n| Documentary\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates]]''\n| Tatiana\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2017\n| ''Take My Nose... Please!''\n| Herself\n| Documentary\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Little Hours]]''\n| Fernanda \n| Also producer\n|<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/the-little-hours-jeff-baena-alison-brie-aubrey-plaza-dave-franco-concourse-film-trade-sales-cannes-1201744271/ |title=Jeff Baena's 'The Little Hours' Acquired By Concourse; Alison Brie, Dave Franco Star \u2013 Cannes |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=April 26, 2016 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref> \n|-\n|''[[Ingrid Goes West]]''\n| Ingrid Thorburn\n| Also producer\n|\n|- \n|2018\n| ''[[An Evening with Beverly Luff Linn]]''\n| Lulu Danger\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Child's Play (2019 film)|Child's Play]]''\n| Karen Barclay\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/09/20/childs-play-reboot-aubrey-plaza-brian-tyree-henry/ |title=Aubrey Plaza, Brian Tyree Henry join 'Child's Play' reboot |work=EW.com |access-date=2018-09-20 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2020\n| ''[[Black Bear (film)|Black Bear]]''\n| Allison\n| \n| <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/aubrey-plaza-christopher-abbott-sarah-gadon-black-bear-director-lawrence-michael-levine-1202656521/ |title=Aubrey Plaza, Christopher Abbott & Sarah Gadon To Star In \u2018Black Bear\u2019 Thriller From Lawrence Michael Levine |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=July 29, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Happiest Season]]''\n| Riley\n| ''Post-production''\n| <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mary-steenburgen-dan-levy-join-kristen-stewart-gay-rom-1271978 |title=Mary Steenburgen, Dan Levy Join Kristen Stewart in Gay Rom-Com 'Happiest Season' |last=Galuppo |first=Mia |date=January 22, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''King Knight ''\n| Pine Cone (voice)\n|  post-production\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|TBA\n| ''[[Best Sellers (film)|Best Sellers]]''\n|\n| ''Post-production''\n| <ref>[https://deadline.com/2019/11/aubrey-plaza-best-sellers-movie-cast-michael-caine-1202778455/ Aubrey Plaza Joins Michael Caine In \u2018Best Sellers\u2019]</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Ark and the Aardvark]]''\n|Brain\n|Voice role; ''In production''\n|<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNary |first=Dave |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/aubrey-plaza-jenny-slate-miles-teller-ark-and-the-aardvark-animated-movie-1202559477/ |title=Aubrey Plaza, Jenny Slate Join Miles Teller's 'Ark and the Aardvark' Animated Movie |date=2017-09-14 |work=Variety |access-date=2018-09-20 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Hope''\n|Hope\n|Also producer; ''Announced''\n|<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/jackie-van-beek-and-madeleine-sami-to-direct-aubrey-plaza-in-feature-comedy-hope-for-netflix/ |title=Jackie Van Beek and Madeleine Sami to Direct Aubrey Plaza in Feature Comedy \"Hope\" for Netflix |date=2019-08-15 |work=Netflix Media Center |access-date=2020-02-26 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[30 Rock]]''\n| [[NBC page]]\n| Episode: \"[[Tracy Does Conan]]\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132015\n| ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''\n| [[April Ludgate]]\n| 124 episodes<br/>Nominated\u2014[[ALMA Award]] for Favorite TV Actress\u2014Supporting Role <small>(2011)</small><br>Nominated\u2014[[ALMA Award]] for Favorite TV Actress\u2014Leading Role In A Comedy <small>(2012)</small><br>Nominated\u2014[[Imagen Awards|Imagen Award]] for Best Supporting Actress\u2014Television <small>(2010, 2012\u20132013)</small>\n|-\n|2011\n| ''[[Portlandia (TV series)|Portlandia]]''\n| Beth / Bookstore Customer\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[NTSF:SD:SUV::]]''\n| The Rememberer\n| Episode: \"Wasila Hills Cop\"\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014\n| ''[[The Legend of Korra]]''\n| Eska (voice)\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2013\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Sacagawea]]\n| Episode: \"Nashville\"\n|-\n| ''[[Maron (TV series)|Maron]]''\n| Herself\n| Episode: \"Jen Moves to L.A.\"\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[Welcome to Sweden (2014 TV series)|Welcome to Sweden]]''\n| Herself\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[Golan the Insatiable]]''\n| [[Golan the Insatiable#Main characters|Dylan Beekler]] (voice)\n| 6 episodes \n|-\n| ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''\n| Lucy (voice)\n| Uncredited<br/>4 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2016\n| ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''\n| Nocturna (voice)\n| Episode: \"Mall Girl Pearl\"\n|-\n| ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|Comedy Bang! Bang!]]''\n| Lady Aubrey / Herself\n| Episode: \"Aubrey Plaza Wears a Velvet Off-the-Shoulder Gown With Flowers in Her Hair\"\n|-\n| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars (season 2)|RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]''\n| Herself (guest judge)\n|Episode: \"Family That Drags Together\"\n|-\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Aaron Burr]]\n| Episode: \"Hamilton\"\n|-\n| ''[[HarmonQuest]]''\n| Hawaiian Coffee\n| Episode: \"Manoa Prison Hole\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132020\n| ''[[Criminal Minds]]''\n| Cat Adams\n| 4 episodes \n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Legion (TV series)|Legion]]''\n| [[Shadow King|Amahl Farouk / Shadow King]]<br/>[[Legion (TV series)#Lenny Busker|Lenny Busker]]\n| 27 episodes<br/>Nominated\u2014[[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain]] <small>(2018)</small><br>Nominated\u2014[[Imagen Awards|Imagen Award]] for Best Actress\u2014Television <small>(2018)</small>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Easy (TV series)|Easy]]''\n| Lindsay\n| Episode: \"Package Thief\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2019\n| ''[[34th Independent Spirit Awards]]''\n| Herself (host)\n| Television special\n|-\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Cleopatra]]\n| Episode: \"Bad Blood\"\n|-\n| 2019-2020\n| ''[[Crank Yankers]]''\n| Bernadette (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[35th Independent Spirit Awards]]''\n| Herself (host)\n| Television special\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist(s)\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2012\n|\"Hollywood Cemetery Forever Sings\"\n|[[Father John Misty]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KtOToiIDNRA |title=Father John Misty \u2013 Hollywood Forever Cemetery Sings [OFFICIAL VIDEO] |last=Father John Misty |date=January 26, 2012 |publisher=Youtube.com |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n|Girl\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|\"Rouse Yourself\"\n|[[JC Brooks & the Uptown Sound|JC Brooks & The Uptown Sound]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hupdAoeHDjI |title=Rouse Yourself |last=JCBrooksVEVO |date=June 21, 2013 |publisher=[[JC Brooks & the Uptown Sound]] |access-date=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|Girl\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|\"Bona Fide\"\n|Cassorla<ref name=\"tbs\" />\n|Woman in Boat\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aubrey Plaza}}\n* {{Twitter|evilhag}}\n* {{IMDb name|2201555|Aubrey Plaza}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plaza, Aubrey}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Wilmington, Delaware]]\n[[Category:Actresses of British descent]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Delaware]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Upright Citizens Brigade Theater performers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress, comedian}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aubrey Plaza\n| image              = Aubrey Plaza by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Plaza at the 2019 [[WonderCon]]\n| birth_name         = Aubrey Christina Plaza\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1984|06|26}}\n| birth_place        = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| education          = [[Ursuline Academy (Delaware)|Ursuline Academy]]\n| alma_mater         = [[New York University]]\n| occupation         = Actress, comedian, producer\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Jeff Baena]] (2011\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Aubrey Christina Plaza'''<ref name=\"bullett\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bullettmedia.com/article/aubrey-plaza-finally-confronts-her-multiple-personalities/ |title=Aubrey Plaza Finally Confronts Her Multiple Personalities |last=Plaza |first=Aubrey |date=March 1, 2012 |website=Bullett Magazine}}</ref> (born June 26, 1984)<ref>{{Cite news |last=Olsen |first=Mark |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2009/aug/03/entertainment/et-plaza3 |title=Aubrey Plaza: Funny person |date=August 3, 2009 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}} \u2013 interview lists her as 25</ref> is an American actress, comedian and producer. She began her career performing [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[sketch comedy]] at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]]. She received further recognition for her starring role as [[April Ludgate]] on the [[NBC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' (2009\u20132015). From 2017 to 2019, Plaza starred as [[Shadow King|Amahl Farouk / Shadow King]] and [[Legion (TV series)#Lenny Busker|Lenny Busker]] in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] drama series ''[[Legion (TV series)|Legion]]''.\n\nAfter several supporting roles in various films, Plaza had her first leading role as Darius Britt in the comedy ''[[Safety Not Guaranteed]]'' (2012). She also starred in the films ''[[Mystery Team]]'' (2008), ''[[Funny People]]'' (2009), ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'' (2010), ''[[Monsters University]]'' (2013), ''[[Life After Beth]]'' (2014), ''[[Dirty Grandpa]]'' (2016), ''[[Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates]]'' (2016), ''[[The Little Hours]]'' (2017), ''[[Ingrid Goes West]]'' (2017), ''[[An Evening with Beverly Luff Linn]]'' (2018) and ''[[Child's Play (2019 film)|Child's Play]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life==\nPlaza was born in [[Wilmington, Delaware]], to Bernadette, an attorney, and David Plaza, a financial advisor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.delawareonline.com/pulpculture/2010/01/15/from-wilmy-to-hollywood/ |title=From Wilmy to Hollywood |last=Cormier |first=Ryan |date=January 15, 2010 |website=Delaware Online |publisher=[[The News Journal]]}}</ref> She has two younger sisters, Renee and Natalie.<ref name=\"delawaretoday\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.delawaretoday.com/Delaware-Today/March-2012/Aubrey-Plaza-of-NBCs-Parks-and-Recreation-Wilmington-Native-Is-Building-a-Buzz-in-Hollywood/ |title=Aubrey Plaza of NBC's Parks and Recreation: Wilmington Native Is Building a Buzz in Hollywood |last=John Micklos Jr. |date=February 16, 2012 |publisher=Delaware Today}}</ref>\n\nPlaza was named after the song \"[[Aubrey (song)|Aubrey]]\" by [[Bread (band)|Bread]].<ref name=\"delawaretoday.com\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.delawaretoday.com/Delaware-Today/March-2012/Aubrey-Plaza-of-NBCs-Parks-and-Recreation-Wilmington-Native-Is-Building-a-Buzz-in-Hollywood/ |title=Aubrey Plaza of NBC's Parks and Recreation: Wilmington Native Is Building a Buzz in Hollywood |access-date=2018-07-27 |language=en}}</ref> Her father is [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] and her mother is of European-American descent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/girl-slouch-article-1.376882 |title=This girl's no slouch |last=Lee Hern\u00e1ndez |date=June 11, 2009 |website=New York Daily News |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref> Plaza has stated: \"I was like the only diverse kid in my high school, and I'm half-Puerto Rican. But yeah, I have a huge family and tons of cousins in [[Puerto Rico]].\"<ref name=\"latina\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/tv/parks-recreation-star-aubrey-plaza-explains-why-shes-so-hot-right-now |title=''Parks & Recreation'' star Aubrey Plaza explains why she's so hot right now |last=Herrera |first=Monica |date=April 9, 2009 |website=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]}}</ref> Plaza is [[Catholic]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Keller |first=Joel |url=http://parade.com/355704/joelkeller/aubrey-plaza-on-being-grumpy-cat-and-saying-goodbye-to-parks-and-recreation/ |title=Aubrey Plaza on Being Grumpy Cat and Saying Goodbye to 'Parks and Recreation' |work=Parade |access-date=2017-01-06}}</ref>\n\nPlaza graduated from [[Ursuline Academy (Delaware)|Ursuline Academy]], an all-girls [[Catholic school]], in 2002. In high school she was student council president and participated in productions with the Wilmington Drama League.<ref name=\"delawaretoday.com\" /><ref name=\"GQ\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/aubrey-plaza-gq-interview-august-2013 |title=The GQ Interview: Aubrey Plaza |last=Mark Byrne, Todd Cole |date=2013-07-24 |website=GQ |access-date=November 9, 2015}}</ref> She studied film at [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], graduating in 2006.<ref name=\"delawaretoday.com\" />\n\nPlaza suffered a [[stroke]] when she was 20 years old that caused temporary paralysis and [[expressive aphasia]]. Some years later, she had a smaller stroke called a [[transient ischemic attack]] while on the set of ''Parks and Recreation''. She has now fully recovered.<ref name=\"delawaretoday.com\" /><ref>{{Citation |last=Letterman |first=David |title=interview \u2013 \"Late Show with David Letterman\" |date=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0XpTJqNbNIk |title=Aubrey Plaza was clocked in a fist fight! |date=April 4, 2019 |last=Nealon |first=Kevin |type=Videotape |author-link=Kevin Nealon |time=12 minutes 19 seconds |access-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Aubrey Plaza by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Plaza at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n\nPlaza has had many [[internship]]s, and worked as an [[NBC page]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/a13969484/aubrey-plaza-worn-emily-spivack-excerpt/ |title=Aubrey Plaza on the Job That Really Didn't Work Out |date=2017-11-30 |publisher=Elle |access-date=November 30, 2017}}</ref> Plaza has performed [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[sketch comedy]] at the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theater]] since 2004. She also performed stand-up and has appeared at [[Laugh Factory|the Laugh Factory]] and The Improv.\n\nPlaza starred in the online series ''The Jeannie Tate Show'', and starred as Robin Gibney in [[ESPN]]'s ''Mayne Street''. She appeared in the first episode of \"Terrible Decisions with [[Ben Schwartz]]\" on [[Funny or Die]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/76b1d33fb0/terrible-decisions-with-ben-schwartz |title=Terrible Decisions with Ben Schwartz from Eric Appel, Ben Schwartz, and Aubrey Plaza |date=September 27, 2009 |publisher=Funnyordie.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101071219/http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/76b1d33fb0/terrible-decisions-with-ben-schwartz |archive-date=January 1, 2011 |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe played [[Seth Rogen]]'s love interest, Daisy, in 2009's ''[[Funny People]]'' directed by [[Judd Apatow]]. She appeared in ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]'', and [[Derrick Comedy|Derrick Comedy's]] ''[[Mystery Team]]'', which debuted at 2009 [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]. She appeared in a [[CollegeHumor]] short alongside [[Jason Bateman]] and [[Will Arnett]].\n\nShe played [[April Ludgate]] in ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' from 2009 to 2015. For her performance as the deadpan employee, she received universal praise throughout the entire show, being referred to as one of the show's [[breakout character]]s.\n\nOn March 12, 2010, Plaza performed at \"A Night of 140 Tweets: A Celebrity Tweetathon for Haiti\", produced by [[Rob Huebel]], [[Paul Scheer]], [[Ben Stiller]], and Mike Rosenstein, at the Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre in Los Angeles.\n\nIn 2011 she appeared on ''[[Portlandia (TV series)|Portlandia]]''. Plaza appeared as a guest judge during a roast segment on ''[[The Next Food Network Star]]'' in 2011. She appeared in Episode 199 of the ''[[WTF with Marc Maron]]'' podcast. She also had a recurring role as \"the Princess\" in the comedic sci-fi web series ''Troopers'' on [[CollegeHumor]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.collegehumor.com/troopers |title=Troopers Videos on Collegehumor |work=CollegeHumor |access-date=2018-07-08 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aubrey Plaza 2012 Shankbone.JPG|alt=|thumb|Plaza in 2012]]\nIn 2012, she was featured in [[Father John Misty]]'s music video for the song \"Hollywood Forever Cemetery Sings\" from the album ''[[Fear Fun]]'' and in 2014 she was in Cassorla's \"Bona Fide\" video where she also made her [[saxophone]]-playing debut.<ref name=\"tbs\">[http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/la-et-ms-watch-aubrey-plaza-sax-solos-cassorla-bona-fide-video-20140107-story.html \"Watch Aubrey Plaza rip sax solos in Cassorla's 'Bona Fide' video\"]. August Brown, ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', January 7th, 2014. Retrieved February 27th, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Plaza earned her first starring role in a major film, alongside [[Mark Duplass]], in the comedy, ''[[Safety Not Guaranteed]]''. Plaza played Darius, a jaded intern who answers a curious want ad \"seeking a companion for a time traveling adventure\". Her performance in the film was critically acclaimed, and Gary Thompson of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' questioned whether this role was out of her usual \"pretty slacker\" range but found her performance \"compelling\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/20120615_Aubrey_Plaza_shines_in__lsquo_Safety_Not_Guaranteed_.html |title=Aubrey Plaza shines in 'Safety Not Guaranteed' |last=Thompson |first=Gary |date=June 15, 2012 |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |access-date=July 6, 2012 |quote=It's too early to say if Plaza's an actress, since no one's asked her to do anything other than be the pretty slacker with the bored posture and world-weary intonation. But she has an unusual kind of beauty (Anglo-Irish, Latina) that the camera loves to explore, and when she does make the hyperspace jump to sincerity and initiative, the results are compelling.}}</ref>\n\nShe won the award for Breakthrough Performance (Female) at the 2012 [[Young Hollywood Awards]] (YHA).\n\nIn 2013, she had the leading female role as Sacagawea in Drunk History episode ''Nashville'' in the segment on Lewis and Clark Expedition.<ref>{{Citation |last=Comedy Central |title=Drunk History \u2013 Lewis and Clark |date=2013-08-14 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZLGuWyfUH5Y |access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2014 Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2014, Plaza's film, ''[[Life After Beth]]'', which was written and directed by her boyfriend Jeff Baena, premiered.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://inthemixxshow.com/4143/youll-never-guess-aubrey-plazas-kinky-on-set-ritual |title=You'll Never Guess Aubrey Plaza's Kinky On-Set Ritual! |date=October 17, 2013 |publisher=In the Mixx |access-date=June 26, 2014}}</ref> Plaza also voiced [[Grumpy Cat]] in the [[Lifetime Network]]'s original movie ''[[Grumpy Cat's Worst Christmas Ever]]'' (2014).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/09/17/aubrey-plaza-grumpy-cat-lifetime |title=Aubrey Plaza will be the voice of Grumpy Cat in Lifetime movie |last=Blake |first=Emily |date=September 17, 2014 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=September 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe starred in ''[[Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates]]'' alongside [[Zac Efron]], [[Anna Kendrick]] and [[Adam DeVine]]. The film was released on July 8, 2016. Her role as the rebellious Tatiana earned her critical praise.\n\nIn 2016, she was a guest star on ''[[Harmonquest|HarmonQuest]]'', as a gnome named \"Hawaiian Coffee\" and portrayed [[Aaron Burr]] in the \"Hamilton\" episode of ''[[Drunk History]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/08/see-drunk-historys-new-hamilton-and-burr.html |title=Alia Shawkat and Aubrey Plaza Are Drunk History's New Hamilton and Burr |work=Vulture |access-date=2018-07-27 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe also had the only speaking line in a commercial for the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[iPhone 6s]], demonstrating \"I'm peeking my flight.  I'm not peeking my flight.  I'm peeking my . . . wait, I missed my flight.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/adfreak/aubrey-plaza-quietly-fails-save-free-world-new-iphone-commercial-169718 |title=Aubrey Plaza Quietly Fails to Save the Free World in This New iPhone Commercial It was asking a lot |last=Nudd |first=Tim |date=February 18, 2016 |website=Adweek.com |access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe first played the role of Cat Adams, a contract killer, in Season 11 of the CBS television show ''[[Criminal Minds]]''. She returned to the role in Seasons 12 and 15.\n\nIn 2017, Plaza both starred in and produced two films, ''[[The Little Hours]]'' and ''[[Ingrid Goes West]].'' It was announced that she would star in indie comedy ''[[An Evening with Beverly Luff Linn|An Evening With Beverly Luff Linn]]'' in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/aubrey-plaza-emile-hirsch-evening-with-beverly-luff-linn-1201981457/ |title=Aubrey Plaza, Emile Hirsch to Star in Indie Comedy 'An Evening With Beverly Luff Linn' |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=2017-02-08 |website=Variety |access-date=February 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPlaza starred as both [[Shadow King|Amahl Farouk / Shadow King]] and Lenny Busker in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] series ''[[Legion (TV series)|Legion]]'' from 2017 to 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2016/02/04/legion-dan-stevens-cast-aubrey-plaza-x-men-series-fx/ |title=Legion: Dan Stevens to Play Charles Xavier's Son; Aubrey Plaza Also Cast |last=Swift |first=Andy |last2=Swift |first2=Andy |date=2016-02-04 |website=TVLine |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref> On February 23, 2019, Plaza hosted the [[34th Independent Spirit Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/aubrey-plaza-host-2019-film-independent-spirit-awards-1164200 |title=Aubrey Plaza to Host 2019 Film Independent Spirit Awards |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, she starred in [[Child's Play (2019 film)|''Child's Play'']], a reboot of the [[Child's Play (1988 film)|1988 film]], as Karen Barclay, Andy\u2019s mother who brings home a killer doll, [[Chucky (character)|Chucky]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.avclub.com/aubrey-plaza-brian-tyree-henry-join-child-s-play-reboo-1829201754 |title=Aubrey Plaza, Brian Tyree Henry join Child's Play reboot |last=Shoemaker |first=Allison |website=News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Plaza starred alongside [[Bill Murray]] in a short parody of [[Robert Eggers]]' [[The Lighthouse (2019 film)|The Lighthouse]] in order to promote the upcoming [[Independent Spirit Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/film/bill-murray-aubrey-plaza-parody-the-lighthouse-2604939 |title=Watch Bill Murray and Aubrey Plaza uncannily parody 'The Lighthouse' |date=2020-02-04 |website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPlaza dated actor [[John Gallagher Jr.]] when they were both 15 years old.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/07/newsroom-john-gallagher-jr-interview.html |title=John Gallagher Jr. on Pratfalls and dating Aubrey Plaza}}</ref> Plaza has been in a long-term relationship with writer and director [[Jeff Baena]] since 2011. They live together in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and work together often.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Spencer |first=Amy |url=https://nypost.com/2017/02/08/aubrey-plaza-like-youve-never-seen-her-before/ |title=Aubrey Plaza like you've never seen her before |date=February 8, 2017 |work=New York Post |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Russell |first=Anna |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/07/03/jeff-baena-and-aubrey-plazas-medieval-adventure |title=Jeff Baena and Aubrey Plaza's Medieval Adventure |date=June 26, 2017 |work=The New Yorker |access-date=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"Comedy\"|Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2006\n| ''Killswitch''\n| Girl with Head Wound\n| Short film\n|\n|-\n| ''In Love''\n| Julie\n| Short film\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2009\n| ''[[Mystery Team]]''\n| Kelly Peters\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Funny People]]''\n| Daisy Danby\n|\n|\n|-\n|2010\n| ''[[Scott Pilgrim vs. the World]]''\n|[[Julie Powers]]\n|\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2011\n| ''[[Damsels in Distress (film)|Damsels in Distress]]''\n| Debbie\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Someday This Pain Will Be Useful to You (film)|Someday This Pain Will Be Useful to You]]''\n| Jeanine Breemer\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[10 Years (2011 film)|10 Years]]''\n| Olivia\n|\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2012\n| ''[[Safety Not Guaranteed]]''\n| Darius Britt\n| \n|\n|-\n| ''[[A Glimpse Inside the Mind of Charles Swan III]]''\n| Marnie\n|\n| <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118043994 |title=Aubrey Plaza joins cast of 'Charlie Swan' |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |date=October 5, 2011 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=8|2013\n| ''[[