anic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Upright Citizens Brigade Theater performers]]\n", "name_user": "Milo76767676676767", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aubrey_Plaza"}
{"title_page": "The Tank (theater)", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = The Tank\n| image = The Tank exterior, September 2018.jpg\n| image_alt=A yellow brick building with two double glass doors, one to the left, the other to the right, runs out of the frame at the top. A person is entering through the left glass doors. A black and white banner hangs from the second story with The Tank's logo and the words \"THE TANK\".\n| image_caption= The Tank's entrance (left), 2018\n| logo_image             = The Tank logo.jpg\n| logo_caption           = The Tank's logo\n| address                = 312 West 36th Street, Manhattan, New York\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.7535298|-73.9932606|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} \n| type                   = [[Off-off-Broadway]]\n| genre                  = Dance, theater, music, film, comedy\n| opened                 = {{Start date|2003|05}} \n| website                =  {{URL|thetanknyc.org}}\n}}\n'''The Tank''' is a nonprofit [[off-off-Broadway]] performance venue and producer in Manhattan, New York. The organization was founded in May 2003 and has since moved several times, currently residing on 36th Street. The Tank presents art across several disciplines (comedy, dance, theater, music, film), produced at no fee for use of the venue to the presenting artists. In addition to its space in Manhattan, The Tank has produced shows performed elsewhere throughout New York City, collectively presenting over 800 performances each year. Programming at the theater is currently suspended due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==History==\nThe Tank was founded in May 2003 in [[Manhattan]], New York, by eight artists, all recent college graduates in their mid-20s.<ref name=\"rail\">{{cite news|last1=Hodges|first1=Mary Love|title=Spotlight on The Tank|url=http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Brooklyn Rail]]|date=February 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063126/http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|archivedate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"harv\">{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Craig|title=Avant-Garde Incubator|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=March\u2013April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809010232/http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|archivedate=August 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spirit\">{{cite news|title=Downtown Edge in Midtown Venue|last1=Eichna|first1=Charlotte|work=West Side Spirit|date=June 17, 2004|page=26}}</ref> Its founders, mostly graduates of [[Yale University]], [[Oberlin College]], and [[Harvard University]], included playwright [[Amy Herzog]], playwright and director [[Alex Timbers]], Justin Krebs, Rachel Levy, Mike Rosenthal, and Randy Bell, who collectively expressed the goal of offering young artists across disciplines the space to create work in the center of New York City.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /><ref name=\"theasy2013\">{{cite news|title=The Tank: A Theasy Interview with Josh Luxenberg, curator of the Flint & Tinder theater series at The Tank|url=http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013063555/http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|archivedate=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"trib\">{{cite news|title=Subterranean 'Tank' Hosts New Music|last1=Pinto|first1=Nick|page=43|date=February 2008|work=[[The Tribeca Trib]]|accessdate=June 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908003153/http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|url=http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|archivedate=September 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe organization was first housed on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth]] and [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth]] Avenues.<ref name=\"spirit\" /> The Tank leased the space on a month-to-month basis from a landlord who intended to sell the building in which the theater was housed, and within 10 months, they had repaid their startup loans. The company derived its name from the architecture of its first space: three large windows overlooking 42nd Street led to someone calling the space The Fishtank and later the ''Fish'' was dropped in favor of The Tank.<ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /> By 2006, the company had moved twice and by 2007, it had won an unsolicited grant of $10,000 from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]] and was receiving money from the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"harv\" /> The Tank's third location, into which it moved in 2006, was on [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]] in the [[Tribeca]] neighborhood, where the organization shared space with [[Collective:Unconscious]] as late as 2008.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Williams|editor1-first=James R.|title=Inside New York 2008|date=2007|publisher=Inside New York|location=New York City|isbn=978-1892768407|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtY1xdbFJz0C&pg=PA158}}</ref>\n\nBy 2010, The Tank had returned to Manhattan's midtown [[Theater District, Manhattan|Theater District]], occupying the [[Davenport Theatre]] on 45th Street between [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth]] and Ninth Avenues.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=La Rocco |first1=Claudia |title=A Long Swim Looking for Laughs |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 5, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328001030/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |archivedate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The Tank had moved to 46th Street by 2013, where it resided until 2017.<ref name=\"theasy2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Heins|first1=Scott|title=5 Fun Things To Do In NYC This Week|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129015925/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> That year, The Tank signed a ten-year, $18,000/month lease on and moved to a two-stage venue on 36th Street, the former home of Abingdon Theatre Company, with one 56-seat [[black box theater]] and one 98-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]].<ref name=\"tm move\">{{cite news|last1=Fujishima|first1=Kenji|title=The Tank Announces New Season, New Home|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=August 25, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225955/http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"playbill new home\">{{cite news|last1=Clement|first1=Olivia|title=The Tank Finds New Home in Old Abingdon Theatre Company Space|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914172942/http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|archivedate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"vv 2017 move\">{{cite news|last1=Felton-Dansky|first1=Miriam|title=This Fall, Rent-Challenged Downtown Theaters Are Battling to Stay in Place|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=September 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913052850/https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|archivedate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite news |last1=Stiffler |first1=Scott |title=Rising rents push NYC theater companies to get creative to secure real estate |url=https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[AM New York]] |date=September 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904233254/https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |archivedate=September 4, 2019}}</ref> The Chain Theater, Workshop Theater, and [[the Barrow Group]] also reside in the same building as The Tank.<ref name=\"amny\" /> The Tank's move coincided with the relocations of several other New York City theaters in mid-2017, including [[the Flea Theater]] and the Chocolate Factory.<ref name=\"vv 2017 move\" />\n\nIn 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], The Tank laid off most of its staff and suspended programming beginning March 13, canceling 109 performances for an estimated loss of $50,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snook |first1=Raven |title=Beyond Broadway: Which Shows Are Suspended, Permanently Closed or Still Running? |url=https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Theatre Development Fund]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314005835/https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Helen |title='There Is No \"Surplus\" in Nonprofit': How Off Broadway Is Coping With Closure |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314053843/https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilella |first1=Frank |title=How the Coronavirus Has Impacted Off-Broadway |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[NY1]] |date=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320172526/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |archivedate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While the space is closed, The Tank launched a weekly digital arts [[Live streaming|livestream]] called CyberTank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stigler |first1=Britt |title=The Tank launches new (digital) spaces with an excerpt from Ran Xia |url=https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=All Arts |publisher=[[WNET]] |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318172738/https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tank's artistic director is Meghan Finn as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clement |first1=Olivia |title=Tonya Pinkins Curates Collection of Feminist Plays at The Tank Off-Broadway |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Playbill]] |date=September 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906201352/http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |archivedate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n{{multiple image\n | width = \n | image1 = The Tank - 98 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt1 = A dark proscenium stage illuminated by the glow of purple lights\n | image2 = The Tank - 56 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt2 = A dark three-quarter blackbox theater with seats in front and to both sides, illuminated by pinkish lights\n | footer = The Tank's 98-seat proscenium stage (left) and 56-seat blackbox (right)\n}}\nCategorized as an off-off-Broadway venue, The Tank presents more than 800 performances each year across several disciplines.<ref name=\"open\">{{cite news|last1=Hookey|first1=Sarah|work=[[BroadwayWorld]]|title=All For One Theater premieres Crystal Skillman's Open at The Tank in June|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 30, 2019|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630011710/https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archivedate=June 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Study of Off-Off-Broadway Performance Venues|url=http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|publisher=New York Innovative Theatre Foundation|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160155/http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2015|date=December 2008|accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=New York Innovative Theatre Awards}}</ref> Each discipline\u2013including dance, music, theater, comedy, and film\u2013is curated by one or more curators.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /> Artists do not pay to use the venue and are paid a portion of the ticket sales, a practice made sustainable by surplus value generated by better-selling shows.<ref name=\"rail\" /> As a nonprofit producer, the organization relies heavily on volunteers.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Shoshana|title=Vera & Valya & The Magical One Cat Circus|url=http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=November 15, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129212200/http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Most days, The Tank runs multiple shows in a single night.<ref name=\"rail\" /> In addition to presenting shows at its 36th Street location, artists have also produced pieces with The Tank at other venues in New York City, such as the 3LD Art and Technology Center in Lower Manhattan and Standard ToyKraft in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"cat\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|title=Review: Urban Nightmares as Puppets in 'The Paper Hat Game'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 26, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722150341/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|archivedate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> The theater runs several festivals each summer, including LadyFest and DarkFest, the latter of which requires performers to create shows using no [[stage lighting]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vincentelli |first1=Elisabeth |title=Review: Besties With Rasputin in 'Red Emma and the Mad Monk' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114424/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |archivedate=August 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=van Laarhoven |first1=Kasper |title=Let There Be Dark! at This Electricity-Free Theater Festival |url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=Bedford + Bowery |publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 27, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018074841/http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Village Voice]]'' listed The Tank in its Best of NYC poll in 2004, describing the theater as the city's \"Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout\".<ref name=\"best of nyc\">{{cite news|title=Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout|work=[[The Village Voice]]|page=88|date=October 6\u201312, 2004|last1=Cole|first1=Lori|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041027184720/http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|archivedate=October 27, 2004|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Time Out New York]]'' described The Tank as \"one of NYC's premiere incubators of emerging talent\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldman |first1=Adam |title=The best live theater to watch from home on March 31 |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Time Out New York]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331201548/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |archivedate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant]]'', which premiered at The Tank in 2003, received an [[Obie Award]] special citation in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Ernio|title=''A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant'' Returns to NYC|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954|accessdate=October 3, 2018|work=[[Playbill]]|date=September 15, 2006|archivedate=June 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630052745/http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954}}</ref> In 2007, [[Lucy Alibar]]'s ''Juicy and Delicious'', which would later be adapted into the film ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', had its world premiere at The Tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Gordon |title='Beasts' author has stage roots |url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422153342/https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |archivedate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> Alibar's screenplay would go on to be [[List of accolades received by Beasts of the Southern Wild|nominated]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=85th Academy Award Nominations: 'Beasts of the Southern Wild,' 'Lincoln,' and 'Silver Linings Playbook' Earn Major Recognition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=January 10, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203085713/https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/|archivedate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> The Tank has received six [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. Two shows, ''ADA/AVA'' and ''YOUARENOWHERE'', were nominated in 2016, and another two, ''the ephemera trilogy'' and ''The Paper Hat Game'', were nominated in 2017, all in the category of [[Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience|Unique Theatrical Experience]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Editorial staff|title=''Shuffle Along'', ''The Humans'', and More Take Home 2016 Drama Desk Awards|url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=June 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812083221/http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|archivedate=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title='Hello, Dolly!' And 'The Hairy Ape' Lead Drama Desk Musical, Drama Nominations|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428110204/http://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|archivedate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, [[Sinking Ship Productions]]' ''A Hunger Artist'' received two nominations: [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Solo Performance|Outstanding Solo Performance]] and Outstanding Puppet Design.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Nominees|url=http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|website=Drama Desk Awards|publisher=Drama Desk|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427175821/http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|archivedate=April 27, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--==Selected production history==-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.thetanknyc.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tank, The}}\n[[Category:2003 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Off-Off-Broadway]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in New York City]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = The Tank\n| image = The Tank exterior, September 2018.jpg\n| image_alt=A yellow brick building with two double glass doors, one to the left, the other to the right, runs out of the frame at the top. A person is entering through the left glass doors. A black and white banner hangs from the second story with The Tank's logo and the words \"THE TANK\".\n| image_caption= The Tank's entrance (left), 2018\n| logo_image             = The Tank logo.jpg\n| logo_caption           = The Tank's logo\n| address                = 312 West 36th Street, Manhattan, New York\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.7535298|-73.9932606|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} \n| type                   = [[Off-Off-Broadway]]\n| genre                  = Dance, theater, music, film, comedy\n| opened                 = {{Start date|2003|05}} \n| website                =  {{URL|thetanknyc.org}}\n}}\n'''The Tank''' is a nonprofit [[Off-Off-Broadway]] performance venue and producer in Manhattan, New York. The organization was founded in May 2003 and has since moved several times, currently residing on 36th Street. The Tank presents art across several disciplines (comedy, dance, theater, music, film), produced at no fee for use of the venue to the presenting artists. In addition to its space in Manhattan, The Tank has produced shows performed elsewhere throughout New York City, collectively presenting over 800 performances each year. Programming at the theater is currently suspended due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==History==\nThe Tank was founded in May 2003 in [[Manhattan]], New York, by eight artists, all recent college graduates in their mid-20s.<ref name=\"rail\">{{cite news|last1=Hodges|first1=Mary Love|title=Spotlight on The Tank|url=http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=[[The Brooklyn Rail]]|date=February 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512063126/http://brooklynrail.org/2010/02/dance/spotlight-on-the-tank|archivedate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"harv\">{{cite news|last1=Lambert|first1=Craig|title=Avant-Garde Incubator|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=March\u2013April 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809010232/http://harvardmagazine.com/2007/03/avant-garde-incubator.html|archivedate=August 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"spirit\">{{cite news|title=Downtown Edge in Midtown Venue|last1=Eichna|first1=Charlotte|work=West Side Spirit|date=June 17, 2004|page=26}}</ref> Its founders, mostly graduates of [[Yale University]], [[Oberlin College]], and [[Harvard University]], included playwright [[Amy Herzog]], playwright and director [[Alex Timbers]], Justin Krebs, Rachel Levy, Mike Rosenthal, and Randy Bell, who collectively expressed the goal of offering young artists across disciplines the space to create work in the center of New York City.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /><ref name=\"theasy2013\">{{cite news|title=The Tank: A Theasy Interview with Josh Luxenberg, curator of the Flint & Tinder theater series at The Tank|url=http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|accessdate=January 27, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=June 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013063555/http://www.theasy.com/FeaturedArtist/thetank.php|archivedate=October 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"trib\">{{cite news|title=Subterranean 'Tank' Hosts New Music|last1=Pinto|first1=Nick|page=43|date=February 2008|work=[[The Tribeca Trib]]|accessdate=June 27, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908003153/http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|url=http://www.tribecatrib.com/news/newsfeb08/Tank.html|archivedate=September 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe organization was first housed on [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]] between [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth]] and [[Tenth Avenue (Manhattan)|Tenth]] Avenues.<ref name=\"spirit\" /> The Tank leased the space on a month-to-month basis from a landlord who intended to sell the building in which the theater was housed, and within 10 months, they had repaid their startup loans. The company derived its name from the architecture of its first space: three large windows overlooking 42nd Street led to someone calling the space The Fishtank and later the ''Fish'' was dropped in favor of The Tank.<ref name=\"harv\" /><ref name=\"spirit\" /> By 2006, the company had moved twice and by 2007, it had won an unsolicited grant of $10,000 from the [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]] and was receiving money from the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council.<ref name=\"harv\" /> The Tank's third location, into which it moved in 2006, was on [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church Street]] in the [[Tribeca]] neighborhood, where the organization shared space with [[Collective:Unconscious]] as late as 2008.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Williams|editor1-first=James R.|title=Inside New York 2008|date=2007|publisher=Inside New York|location=New York City|isbn=978-1892768407|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtY1xdbFJz0C&pg=PA158}}</ref>\n\nBy 2010, The Tank had returned to Manhattan's midtown [[Theater District, Manhattan|Theater District]], occupying the [[Davenport Theatre]] on 45th Street between [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth]] and Ninth Avenues.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=La Rocco |first1=Claudia |title=A Long Swim Looking for Laughs |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 5, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328001030/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/06/theater/reviews/the-umbrella-plays-at-the-tank.html |archivedate=March 28, 2019}}</ref> The Tank had moved to 46th Street by 2013, where it resided until 2017.<ref name=\"theasy2013\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Heins|first1=Scott|title=5 Fun Things To Do In NYC This Week|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=[[Gothamist]]|date=January 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129015925/http://gothamist.com/2017/01/16/5_things_jan_2017.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> That year, The Tank signed a ten-year, $18,000/month lease on and moved to a two-stage venue on 36th Street, the former home of Abingdon Theatre Company, with one 56-seat [[black box theater]] and one 98-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]].<ref name=\"tm move\">{{cite news|last1=Fujishima|first1=Kenji|title=The Tank Announces New Season, New Home|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|accessdate=August 28, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=August 25, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225955/http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/the-tank-announces-new-season-home_82204.html|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"playbill new home\">{{cite news|last1=Clement|first1=Olivia|title=The Tank Finds New Home in Old Abingdon Theatre Company Space|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|accessdate=September 14, 2017|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 31, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914172942/http://www.playbill.com/article/the-tank-finds-new-home-in-old-abingdon-theatre-company-space|archivedate=September 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"vv 2017 move\">{{cite news|last1=Felton-Dansky|first1=Miriam|title=This Fall, Rent-Challenged Downtown Theaters Are Battling to Stay in Place|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|accessdate=October 7, 2017|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=September 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913052850/https://www.villagevoice.com/2017/09/12/this-fall-rent-challenged-downtown-theaters-are-battling-to-stay-in-place/|archivedate=September 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"amny\">{{cite news |last1=Stiffler |first1=Scott |title=Rising rents push NYC theater companies to get creative to secure real estate |url=https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[AM New York]] |date=September 4, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904233254/https://www.amny.com/real-estate/theater-real-estate-1.35887030 |archivedate=September 4, 2019}}</ref> The Chain Theater, Workshop Theater, and [[the Barrow Group]] also reside in the same building as The Tank.<ref name=\"amny\" /> The Tank's move coincided with the relocations of several other New York City theaters in mid-2017, including [[the Flea Theater]] and the Chocolate Factory.<ref name=\"vv 2017 move\" />\n\nIn 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]], The Tank laid off most of its staff and suspended programming beginning March 13, canceling 109 performances for an estimated loss of $50,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snook |first1=Raven |title=Beyond Broadway: Which Shows Are Suspended, Permanently Closed or Still Running? |url=https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=[[Theatre Development Fund]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314005835/https://www.tdf.org/stages/article/2356/beyond-broadway-which-shows-are-suspended-permanently-closed-or-still-running |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=Helen |title='There Is No \"Surplus\" in Nonprofit': How Off Broadway Is Coping With Closure |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=March 13, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314053843/https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/there-is-no-surplus-how-off-broadway-theater-is-coping.html |archivedate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dilella |first1=Frank |title=How the Coronavirus Has Impacted Off-Broadway |url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=[[NY1]] |date=March 20, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320172526/https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/arts/2020/03/20/the-coronavirus-impact-on-off-broadway- |archivedate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> While the space is closed, The Tank launched a weekly digital arts [[Live streaming|livestream]] called CyberTank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stigler |first1=Britt |title=The Tank launches new (digital) spaces with an excerpt from Ran Xia |url=https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=All Arts |publisher=[[WNET]] |date=March 18, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318172738/https://allarts.org/2020/03/the-tank-launches-new-digital-spaces-with-an-excerpt-from-ran-xia/ |archivedate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Tank's artistic director is Meghan Finn as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clement |first1=Olivia |title=Tonya Pinkins Curates Collection of Feminist Plays at The Tank Off-Broadway |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Playbill]] |date=September 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906201352/http://www.playbill.com/article/tonya-pinkins-curates-collection-of-feminist-plays-at-the-tank-off-broadway |archivedate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n{{multiple image\n | width = \n | image1 = The Tank - 98 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt1 = A dark proscenium stage illuminated by the glow of purple lights\n | image2 = The Tank - 56 Seat Theater.jpg\n | alt2 = A dark three-quarter blackbox theater with seats in front and to both sides, illuminated by pinkish lights\n | footer = The Tank's 98-seat proscenium stage (left) and 56-seat blackbox (right)\n}}\nCategorized as an Off-Off-Broadway venue, The Tank presents more than 800 performances each year across several disciplines.<ref name=\"open\">{{cite news|last1=Hookey|first1=Sarah|work=[[BroadwayWorld]]|title=All For One Theater premieres Crystal Skillman's Open at The Tank in June|date=March 12, 2019|accessdate=June 30, 2019|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630011710/https://www.broadwayworld.com/off-off-broadway/article/All-For-One-Theater-premieres-Crystal-Skillmans-OPEN-at-The-Tank-in-June-20190312|archivedate=June 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Study of Off-Off-Broadway Performance Venues|url=http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|publisher=New York Innovative Theatre Foundation|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216160155/http://www.nyitawards.com/survey/OOBSpaceReport2.pdf|archivedate=December 16, 2015|date=December 2008|accessdate=January 28, 2017|website=New York Innovative Theatre Awards}}</ref> Each discipline\u2013including dance, music, theater, comedy, and film\u2013is curated by one or more curators.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"harv\" /> Artists do not pay to use the venue and are paid a portion of the ticket sales, a practice made sustainable by surplus value generated by better-selling shows.<ref name=\"rail\" /> As a nonprofit producer, the organization relies heavily on volunteers.<ref name=\"rail\" /><ref name=\"cat\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Shoshana|title=Vera & Valya & The Magical One Cat Circus|url=http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=Theatre Is Easy|date=November 15, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129212200/http://www.theasy.com/Reviews/2016/V/veraandvalyaandthemagicalonecatcircus.php|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref> Most days, The Tank runs multiple shows in a single night.<ref name=\"rail\" /> In addition to presenting shows at its 36th Street location, artists have also produced pieces with The Tank at other venues in New York City, such as the 3LD Art and Technology Center in Lower Manhattan and Standard ToyKraft in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]].<ref name=\"cat\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Brantley|first1=Ben|title=Review: Urban Nightmares as Puppets in 'The Paper Hat Game'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|accessdate=January 29, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 26, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722150341/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/27/theater/review-urban-nightmares-as-puppets-in-the-paper-hat-game.html|archivedate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> The theater runs several festivals each summer, including LadyFest and DarkFest, the latter of which requires performers to create shows using no [[stage lighting]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vincentelli |first1=Elisabeth |title=Review: Besties With Rasputin in 'Red Emma and the Mad Monk' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 21, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830114424/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/21/theater/review-red-emma-and-the-mad-monk-the-tank.html |archivedate=August 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=van Laarhoven |first1=Kasper |title=Let There Be Dark! at This Electricity-Free Theater Festival |url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |accessdate=September 16, 2018 |work=Bedford + Bowery |publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=July 27, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018074841/http://bedfordandbowery.com/2017/07/let-there-be-dark-at-this-electricity-free-theater-festival/ |archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Village Voice]]'' listed The Tank in its Best of NYC poll in 2004, describing the theater as the city's \"Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout\".<ref name=\"best of nyc\">{{cite news|title=Best Broadway theater turned hipster hangout|work=[[The Village Voice]]|page=88|date=October 6\u201312, 2004|last1=Cole|first1=Lori|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041027184720/http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|archivedate=October 27, 2004|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/bestof/2004/detail.php?id=4452|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''[[Time Out New York]]'' described The Tank as \"one of NYC's premiere incubators of emerging talent\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feldman |first1=Adam |title=The best live theater to watch from home on March 31 |url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Time Out New York]] |date=March 31, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331201548/https://www.timeout.com/newyork/theater/the-best-live-theater-to-watch-from-home-march-31 |archivedate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant]]'', which premiered at The Tank in 2003, received an [[Obie Award]] special citation in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernandez|first1=Ernio|title=''A Very Merry Unauthorized Children's Scientology Pageant'' Returns to NYC|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954|accessdate=October 3, 2018|work=[[Playbill]]|date=September 15, 2006|archivedate=June 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630052745/http://www.playbill.com/article/a-very-merry-unauthorized-childrens-scientology-pageant-returns-to-nyc-com-134954}}</ref> In 2007, [[Lucy Alibar]]'s ''Juicy and Delicious'', which would later be adapted into the film ''[[Beasts of the Southern Wild]]'', had its world premiere at The Tank.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Gordon |title='Beasts' author has stage roots |url=https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422153342/https://variety.com/2012/film/news/beasts-author-has-stage-roots-1118056553/ |archivedate=April 22, 2019}}</ref> Alibar's screenplay would go on to be [[List of accolades received by Beasts of the Southern Wild|nominated]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=85th Academy Award Nominations: 'Beasts of the Southern Wild,' 'Lincoln,' and 'Silver Linings Playbook' Earn Major Recognition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/ |accessdate=May 11, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=January 10, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203085713/https://www.slashfilm.com/85th-academy-award-nominations-beasts-of-the-southern-wild-lincoln-and-silver-linings-playbook-earn-major-recognition/|archivedate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> The Tank has received six [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations. Two shows, ''ADA/AVA'' and ''YOUARENOWHERE'', were nominated in 2016, and another two, ''the ephemera trilogy'' and ''The Paper Hat Game'', were nominated in 2017, all in the category of [[Drama Desk Award for Unique Theatrical Experience|Unique Theatrical Experience]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Editorial staff|title=''Shuffle Along'', ''The Humans'', and More Take Home 2016 Drama Desk Awards|url=http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|accessdate=May 14, 2017|work=TheaterMania|date=June 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812083221/http://www.theatermania.com/broadway/news/2016-drama-desk-award-winners_77336.html|archivedate=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gerard|first1=Jeremy|title='Hello, Dolly!' And 'The Hairy Ape' Lead Drama Desk Musical, Drama Nominations|url=https://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|accessdate=May 14, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428110204/http://deadline.com/2017/04/hello-dolly-and-the-hairy-ape-lead-drama-desk-nominations-1202078367/|archivedate=April 28, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, [[Sinking Ship Productions]]' ''A Hunger Artist'' received two nominations: [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Solo Performance|Outstanding Solo Performance]] and Outstanding Puppet Design.<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Nominees|url=http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|website=Drama Desk Awards|publisher=Drama Desk|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427175821/http://dramadeskawards.com/2018-nominees|archivedate=April 27, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n<!--==Selected production history==-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.thetanknyc.org/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tank, The}}\n[[Category:2003 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Off-Off-Broadway]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in New York City]]\n[[Category:Theatres in Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Bobamnertiopsis", "label": "safe", "comment": "off case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tank_(theater)"}
{"title_page": "Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Women's 1500 metres\n|games = 1988 Summer\n|image =\n|caption =\n|venue = [[Olympic Stadium (Seoul)|Olympic Stadium]]\n|dates = {{Date|1988-9-28}} (heats)<br />{{Date|1988-10-1}} (final)\n|competitors = 28\n|nations = 19\n|win_value = 3:53.96 {{OlyR|athletics}}\n|longnames = yes\n|gold = [[Paula Ivan]]\n|goldNOC = ROM\n|silver = [[Laimut\u0117 Baikauskait\u0117]]\n|silverNOC = URS\n|bronze = [[Tetyana Dorovskikh|Tetyana Samolenko]]\n|bronzeNOC = URS\n|prev = [[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1984]]\n|next = [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1992]]\n}}\n{{AthleticsAt1988SummerOlympics}}\n\nThe '''women's 1500 metres''' at the [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul, South Korea]] had an entry list of 28 competitors, with two qualifying heats (28) before the final (12) took place on Saturday October 1, 1988.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1988/ATH/womens-1500-metres.html |title=Athletics at the 1988 Seoul Games: Women's 1500 metres |accessdate=1 November 2017 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom the gun in the final, [[Paula Ivan]] wanted the lead.  [[Mary Slaney]] and Ivan's teammate [[Doina Melinte]] didn't want to let her get away.  The field behind her looked bunched but the 1:02.52 first lap showed she was serious.  This was world record pace, rare for a championship race that usually breaks down into a strategic battle.  After the first lap, a small gap began to open.  Melinte was the last to maintain contact, perhaps having seen this strategy previously in domestic competition.  The second lap was completed in 1:03.26, a ten-metre gap had opened, with [[Tetyana Dorovskikh|Tetyana Samolenko]] edging past Melinte in chase.  2:52.66 at the bell and a fifteen-metre gap, Ivan began a last lap [[Kick (running)|kick]], trying to run the 60 second last lap to get the world record.  Because of the acceleration, the third lap was the fastest of them all at 1:02.46.  The battle was for the medals behind Ivan, [[Andrea Hahmann]] passing Samolenko, who had [[Christina Boxer|Christina Cahill]] on her shoulder with Lynn Williams in chase.  Melinte faded back to Slaney but behind all of them, [[Laimut\u0117 Baikauskait\u0117]] was charging.  Onto the home stretch the chase pack was tightening, some 30 metres behind Ivan.  Baikauskait\u0117 moved into lane 3 to find some running room.  Ivan wasn't able to find a 60-second lap, 61.5 was enough to set the [[List of Olympic records in athletics|Olympic record]] out of sight with a dominant gold medal performance.  Hahmann faded and Samolenko was leading down the stretch with Cahill in close pursuit.  Making up ten metres on the final straight, Baikauskait\u0117 passed Cahill and Hahmann in the final 15 metres and leaned past Samolenko at the line to take the silver.\n\n==Medalists==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|-\n|{{OlympicGoldMedalist|[[Paula Ivan]]|ROU|1988 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicSilverMedalist|[[Laimut\u0117 Baikauskait\u0117]]|URS|1988 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicBronzeMedalist|[[Tetyana Dorovskikh|Tetyana Samolenko]]|URS|1988 Summer}}\n|}\n\n==Records==\nThese were the standing world and Olympic records (in minutes) prior to the 1988 Summer Olympics.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- \n! World Record\n| 3:52.47\n| {{flagicon|URS}} [[Tatyana Kazankina]]\n| [[Z\u00fcrich]] ([[Switzerland|SUI]])\n| August 13, 1980\n|-\n! Olympic Record\n| 3:56.56\n| {{flagicon|URS}} [[Tatyana Kazankina]]\n| [[Moscow]] ([[Soviet Union|URS]])\n| August 1, 1980\n|}\n\nThe following Olympic record (in minutes) was set during this competition.\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|-\n!Date !! Athlete !! Time !! OR !! WR\n|-\n|September 26, 1988||align=left| {{flagIOCathlete|[[Paula Ivan]]|ROM|1988 Summer}} ||'''3:53.96'''|| OR ||\n|}\n\n==Final==\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"width: 20em\"|FINAL\n!style=\"width: 5em\"|TIME\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Med 1.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Paula Ivan]]|ROU|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''3:53.96'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Med 2.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Laimut\u0117 Baikauskait\u0117]]|URS|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:00.24'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Med 3.png]]\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Tetyana Dorovskikh|Tetyana Samolenko]]|URS|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:00.30'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|4.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Christina Boxer|Christina Cahill]]|GBR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:00.64'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|5.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Lynn Williams (athlete)|Lynn Williams]]|CAN|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:00.86'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|6.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Andrea Hahmann]]|GDR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:00.96'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|7.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Shireen Bailey]]|GBR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:02.32'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|8.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Mary Slaney]]|USA|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:02.49'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|9.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Doina Melinte]]|ROU|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:02.89'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|10.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Fatima Aouam]]|MAR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:08.00'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|11.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kim Gallagher]]|USA|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:16.25'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|12.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Debbie Bowker]]|CAN|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:17.95'''\n|}\n\n==Non-Qualifiers==\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"width: 20em\"|NON-QUALIFIERS\n!style=\"width: 5em\"|TIME\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|13.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Elly van Hulst]]|NED|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:07.40'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|14.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hassiba Boulmerka]]|ALG|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:08.33'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|15.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kirsty Wade]]|GBR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:08.37'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|16.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Lyubov Gurina]]|URS|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:08.59'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|17.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Angela Chalmers]]|CAN|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:08.64'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|18.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vera Michallek]]|FRG|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:10.05'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|19.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Susan Sirma]]|KEN|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:10.13'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|20.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Cornelia B\u00fcrki]]|SUI|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:10.89'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|21.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Regina Jacobs]]|USA|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:18.09'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|22.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Letitia Vriesde]]|SUR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:19.58'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|23.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Khin Khin Htwe]]|BIR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:20.92'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|24.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[No Hye-sun]]|KOR|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:26.05'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|25.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Daphrose Nyiramutuzo]]|RWA|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:32.31'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|26.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Laverne Bryan]]|ANT|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:39.73''' \n|-\n|align=\"center\"|27.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Poloni Avek]]|PNG|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''4:46.49'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|28.\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Rachel Thompson]]|SLE|1988 Summer}}\n|align=\"center\" |'''5:31.42'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1987 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|